{"title_page": "Alfred W. Place", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Alfred W. Place\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1877|5|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Rudolph, Ohio]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1955|9|19|1877|5|8}}\n| death_place = [[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1899\u20131900\n| player_team1 = [[Chicago Maroons football|Chicago]]\n| player_positions = [[End (gridiron football)|End]], [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]]\n| coach_years1 = 1903\n| coach_team1 = [[Akron Zips football|Buchtel]]\n| overall_record = 0\u20132\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Alfred William Place''' (May 8, 1877 \u2013 September 19, 1955) was an [[American football]] player and coach, minister, and missionary.  He was the sixth head football coach at Buchtel College\u2014now known as the [[University of Akron]]\u2014helming the team for one season in 1903 and compiling a record of 0\u20132.  Place played [[college football]] as a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] at the [[University of Chicago]].  He was a missionary in Japan from 1907 to 1913.  Place died on September 19, 1955, at Methodist Hospital in [[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, Indiana]]. from injuries he sustained while was blasting  tree stumps on his farm near [[Mooresville, Indiana]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ex-Missionary Killed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33032391/the_indianapolis_news/ |newspaper=[[The Indianapolis News]] |location=[[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, Indiana]] |date=September 20, 1955 |page=14 |access-date=June 19, 2019 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Akron Zips football|Buchtel]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | starty