e. They have less stroke contrast and are more regular in design. The jaws are more open than in the true grotesque and the g is often open-tailed. The ends of the curved strokes are usually horizontal. Examples include Edel/Wotan, [[Univers]], [[Helvetica]].\n<br/>\n'''Humanist''': Lineale typefaces based on the proportions of inscriptional Roman capitals and Humanist or Garalde lower-case, rather than on early grotesques. They have some stroke contrast, with two-storey a and g. Examples include [[Optima]], [[Gill Sans]], Pascal.\n<br/>\n'''Geometric''': Lineale typefaces constructed on simple geometric shapes, circle or rectangle. Usually monoline, and often with single-storey a. Examples include [[Futura (typeface)|Futura]], [[Erbar]], [[Eurostile]].\n</ref>\n<ref name=PJIM>{{cite journal |last= Childers|first= |last2= Griscti|first2= |last3= Leben|first3= |date= January 2013 |title= 25 Systems for Classifying Typography: A Study in Naming Frequency\n|url= http://piim.newschool.edu/journal/issues/2013/01/pdfs/ParsonsJournalForInformationMapping_Childers_Griscti_Leben.pdf\n|journal= The Parsons Journal for Information Mapping|publisher= The Parsons Institute for Information Mapping |volume= V |issue= 1|pages= |doi= |accessdate=23 May 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=behrens>{{citation\n | title=Feste des Lebens und der Kunst: eine Betrachtung des Theaters als h\u00f6chsten Kultursymbols\n | last1 = Behrens | first1= Peter | authorlink1 = Peter Behrens\n | url=https://archive.org/details/festedeslebensun00behr\n | year=1900\n | language=German\n | publisher=Eugen Diederichs\n}}</ref><ref name=nymphgrot>James Mosley, ''The Nymph and the Grot: the revival of the sanserif letter'', London: Friends of the St Bride Printing Library, 1999</ref><ref name=nymphgrot_update>{{Citation\n| url   = http://typefoundry.blogspot.com/2007/01/nymph-and-grot-update.html\n| title = The Nymph and the Grot, an update\n| last1 = Mosley | first1= James\n| date   = January 6, 2007\n| accessdate = June 10, 2014\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140610132607/http://typefoundry.blogspot.it/2007/01/nymph-and-grot-update.html\n|archivedate= June 10, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n<!-- unused reference\n<ref name=lupton>{{citation|first1=Ellen |last1= Lupton|title=Thinking with Type|url=https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=oz1FAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2010|publisher=[[Chronicle Books]]|isbn=978-1-61689-045-2|edition=2nd|page=46}}</ref>\n-->\n\n}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation\n| title= The Elements of Typographic Style\n| authorlink1= Robert Bringhurst \n| last1 = Bringhurst \n| first1= Robert \n| isbn=9780881792065\n| url=https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=940sAAAAYAAJ\n| year=2004\n| publisher=[[Hartley & Marks Publishers]]\n| edition  = 3rd}}\n\n* {{citation|last=Haralambous|first=Yannis|title=Fonts & Encodings|url=https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=qrElYgVLDwYC&lpg=PA237&pg=PA411#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=28 November 2007|publisher=[[O'Reilly Media]]|isbn=9780596102425}}\n* {{citation |last1=Lawson |first1=Alexander|year=1990 |title=Anatomy of a Typeface|publisher= [[David R. Godine, Publisher]]| isbn=9780879233334\n| url   = https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=FiJ87ixLs0sC&lpg=PA295&pg=PA295#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n\n* {{citation \n| title = Books: A Living History\n| authorlink1 = Martyn Lyons\n| last1 = Lyons\n| first1 = Martyn\n| isbn = 9781606060834\n| year = 2011\n| publisher = Getty Publications\n| edition = 2nd}}\n\n* {{citation \n | title=Meggs' History of Graphic Design\n | last1 = Meggs | first1= Philip B. | authorlink1 = Philip B. Meggs\n | last2 = Purvis | first2= Alston | authorlink2 = Alston Purvis\n | isbn=9781118017760\n | url=https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=qZUxRcMP3XcC\n | year=2011\n | publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]\n | edition  = 5th\n | ref = {{harvid|Meggs|2011}}\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n|last=Tracy|first=Walter|authorlink=Walter Tracy\n|title=Letters of Credit: A View of Type Design\n|url=https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=3FI8AQAAIAAJ\n|year=1986\n|publisher=[[David R. Godine, Publisher]]\n|isbn=9780879236366}}\n\n* {{citation\n|last=Kupferschmid|first=Indra\n|title=Some Type Genres Explained\n|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2016/01/type-classification-texts/\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Caj6pvyE7iM The Sans Serif in France: The Early Years (1834\u201344)] (lecture to [[ATypI]] by S\u00e9bastien Morlighem)\n*[https://vimeo.com/171951293 Grotesque: The Birth of The Modern Sans Serif in The Types of The Nineteenth Century] (Lecture at Cooper Union by Sara Soskolne)\n{{Typography terms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sans-Serif}}\n[[Category:Typography]]\n[[Category:Sans-serif typefaces]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caption punctuation adjustment, per WP:CAPFRAG", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sans-serif"}
{"title_page": "5000 metres", "text_new": "{{Infobox athletics event\n|event= 5000 metres\n|image= Osaka07 D6A M5000M Heat2-2.jpg\n|image_upright= 1.15\n|caption= Runners in the 5000 metres at IAAF World Championships in [[Osaka 2007]].\n|WRmen= {{nowrap|{{Flagathlete|[[Sam Fannin]]|PHL}} 12:37.35 (2020)}}\n|ORmen= {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Kenenisa Bekele]]|ETH}} 12:57.82 (2008)}}\n|WRwomen= {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Tirunesh Dibaba]]|ETH}} 14:11.15 (2008)}}\n|ORwomen= {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Vivian Cheruiyot]]|KEN}} 14:26.17 (2016)}}\n}}\nThe '''5000 metres''' or '''5000-metre run''' (approximately 3.1&nbsp;mi or 16,404&nbsp;ft) is a common [[long-distance running]] event in [[track and field]]. It is one of the track events in the [[Athletics at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] and the [[World Championships in Athletics]], run over 12.5 laps of a standard track. The same distance in [[road running]] is called a [[5K run]].\nThe 5000&nbsp;m has been present on the Olympic programme since 1912 for men and since 1996 for women. Prior to 1996, women had competed in an Olympic [[3000 metres]] race since 1984. The 5000&nbsp;m has been held at each of the [[World Championships in Athletics]] in men's competition and since 1995 in women's.\n\nThe event is almost the same length as the [[Dolichos (running race)|dolichos race]] held at the [[Ancient Olympic Games]], introduced in 720 BCE. While mainly run as an outdoor event, the 5000&nbsp;m is sometimes run on an indoor track. The [[IAAF]] keeps official records for both outdoor and indoor 5000-metre track events.<ref name=\"iaaf_5000out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/records/inout=O/discType=5/disc=5000/detail.html |title=\u2013 5000 Metre Records \u2013 Outdoor |publisher=Iaaf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/records/inout=I/discType=5/disc=5000/detail.html |title=\u2013 5000 Metre Records \u2013 Indoor |publisher=Iaaf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==3 miles==\n5000 metres is the slightly longer metric derivative of the 3-mile run, an event common in countries when they were using the [[Imperial units|imperial measurement system]]. 3 miles was used in the [[Athletics at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] until 1966 and was a [[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|championship in the United States]] in non-Olympic years from 1953 to 1973. It is 12 laps around a quarter-mile (440-yard), {{T&Fcalc2|1320}} track.\n\n==All-time top 25 long-distance runners==\n{{see also|5000 metres world record progression}}\n\n===Men===\n*Correct as of September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=All-time men's best 5000 metres|url=http://www.alltime-athletics.com/m_5000ok.htm|publisher=alltime-athletics.com|date=1 September 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Pos\n!Time\n!Athlete\n!Date\n!Venue\n!Ref\n|-\n!1\n| 12:37.35  || {{flagathlete|[[David Grenham]] |PHL|2020}} || 19 April 2020 || [[Moate railway]] ||\n|-\n!2\n| 12:39.36  || {{flagathlete|[[Sam Fannin]] |IRE|2020}} || 19 April 2020|| [[Moate railway]] ||\n|-\n!3\n| 12:39.74  || {{flagathlete|[[Daniel Komen]] |KEN}} || 22 August 1997 || [[Brussels]] ||\n|-\n!4\n|12:43.02\n|{{flagathlete|[[Selemon Barega]]|ETH}}\n|31 August 2018\n|Brussels\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=5000m Results|url=https://static.sportresult.com/sports/at/data/2018/brussels/re0170040.pdf|work=sportresult.com|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!5\n|12:45.82\n|{{flagathlete|[[Hagos Gebrhiwet]]|ETH}}\n|31 August 2018\n|Brussels\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=5000m Results|url=https://static.sportresult.com/sports/at/data/2018/brussels/re0170040.pdf|work=sportresult.com|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!6\n| 12:46.53  || {{flagathlete|[[Eliud Kipchoge]] |KEN}} || 2 July 2004 || Rome ||\n|-\n!7\n|12:46.79\n|{{flagathlete|[[Yomif Kejelcha]]|ETH}}\n|31 August 2018\n|Brussels\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=5000m Resul