014\n|-\n|[[1963 in athletics (track and field)|1963]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n|[[1962 in athletics (track and field)|1962]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n|[[1961 in athletics (track and field)|1961]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n|[[1960 in athletics (track and field)|1960]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n*\"i\" indicates indoor performance.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Athletics}}\n* [[National champions 5000 metres (men)]]\n* [[National champions 5000 metres (women)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://iaaf.gekko.de/?a=middle-long&d=5000-metres IAAF list of 5000-metres records in XML]\n*[https://arrs.run/YR_O5K.htm ARRS: Yearly Rankings \u2013 5000 metres Outdoor Track]\n*[http://www.mastersathletics.net/fileadmin/html/Rankings/All_Time/5000metresmen.htm All-time Masters men's 5000 m list]\n*[http://www.mastersathletics.net/fileadmin/html/Rankings/All_Time/5000metreswomen.htm All-time Masters women's 5000 m list]\n\n{{Athletics events}}\n{{Portal bar|Athletics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5000 Metres}}\n[[Category:Events in track and field]]\n[[Category:Long-distance running distances]]\n[[Category:Summer Olympic disciplines in athletics]]\n[[Category:5000 metres| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox athletics event\n|event= 5000 metres\n|image= Osaka07 D6A M5000M Heat2-2.jpg\n|image_upright= 1.15\n|caption= Runners in the 5000 metres at IAAF World Championships in [[Osaka 2007]].\n|WRmen= {{nowrap|{{Flagathlete|[[David Grenham]]|PHL}} 12:37.35 (2020)}}\n|ORmen= {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Kenenisa Bekele]]|ETH}} 12:57.82 (2008)}}\n|WRwomen= {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Tirunesh Dibaba]]|ETH}} 14:11.15 (2008)}}\n|ORwomen= {{nowrap|{{flagathlete|[[Vivian Cheruiyot]]|KEN}} 14:26.17 (2016)}}\n}}\nThe '''5000 metres''' or '''5000-metre run''' (approximately 3.1&nbsp;mi or 16,404&nbsp;ft) is a common [[long-distance running]] event in [[track and field]]. It is one of the track events in the [[Athletics at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] and the [[World Championships in Athletics]], run over 12.5 laps of a standard track. The same distance in [[road running]] is called a [[5K run]].\nThe 5000&nbsp;m has been present on the Olympic programme since 1912 for men and since 1996 for women. Prior to 1996, women had competed in an Olympic [[3000 metres]] race since 1984. The 5000&nbsp;m has been held at each of the [[World Championships in Athletics]] in men's competition and since 1995 in women's.\n\nThe event is almost the same length as the [[Dolichos (running race)|dolichos race]] held at the [[Ancient Olympic Games]], introduced in 720 BCE. While mainly run as an outdoor event, the 5000&nbsp;m is sometimes run on an indoor track. The [[IAAF]] keeps official records for both outdoor and indoor 5000-metre track events.<ref name=\"iaaf_5000out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/records/inout=O/discType=5/disc=5000/detail.html |title=\u2013 5000 Metre Records \u2013 Outdoor |publisher=Iaaf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/records/inout=I/discType=5/disc=5000/detail.html |title=\u2013 5000 Metre Records \u2013 Indoor |publisher=Iaaf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==3 miles==\n5000 metres is the slightly longer metric derivative of the 3-mile run, an event common in countries when they were using the [[Imperial units|imperial measurement system]]. 3 miles was used in the [[Athletics at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] until 1966 and was a [[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|championship in the United States]] in non-Olympic years from 1953 to 1973. It is 12 laps around a quarter-mile (440-yard), {{T&Fcalc2|1320}} track.\n\n==All-time top 25 long-distance runners==\n{{see also|5000 metres world record progression}}\n\n===Men===\n*Correct as of September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=All-time men's best 5000 metres|url=http://www.alltime-athletics.com/m_5000ok.htm|publisher=alltime-athletics.com|date=1 September 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Pos\n!Time\n!Athlete\n!Date\n!Venue\n!Ref\n|-\n!1\n| 12:37.35  || {{flagathlete|[[David Grenham]] |PHL|2020}} || 19 April 2020 || [[Moate railway]] ||\n|-\n!2\n| 12:39.36  || {{flagathlete|[[Sam Fannin]] |IRE|2020}} || 19 April 2020|| [[Moate railway]] ||\n|-\n!3\n| 12:39.74  || {{flagathlete|[[Daniel Komen]] |KEN}} || 22 August 1997 || [[Brussels]] ||\n|-\n!4\n|12:43.02\n|{{flagathlete|[[Selemon Barega]]|ETH}}\n|31 August 2018\n|Brussels\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=5000m Results|url=https://static.sportresult.com/sports/at/data/2018/brussels/re0170040.pdf|work=sportresult.com|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!5\n|12:45.82\n|{{flagathlete|[[Hagos Gebrhiwet]]|ETH}}\n|31 August 2018\n|Brussels\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=5000m Results|url=https://static.sportresult.com/sports/at/data/2018/brussels/re0170040.pdf|work=sportresult.com|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!6\n| 12:46.53  || {{flagathlete|[[Eliud Kipchoge]] |KEN}} || 2 July 2004 || Rome ||\n|-\n!7\n|12:46.79\n|{{flagathlete|[[Yomif Kejelcha]]|ETH}}\n|31 August 2018\n|Brussels\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=5000m Results|url=https://static.sportresult.com/sports/at/data/2018/brussels/re0170040.pdf|work=sportresult.com|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!8\n| 12:46.81  || {{flagathlete|[[Dejen Gebremeskel]] |ETH}} || 6 July 2012 || Paris  || <ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|title=5000 Metres Results|url=http://www.iaaf.org/competitions/dlm/eventcode=4921/sex=M/discCode=5000/result.html#M5000|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=6 July 2012|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n!9\n| 12:47.04  || {{flagathlete|[[Sileshi Sihine]] |ETH|1996}} || 2 July 2004 || Rome ||\n|-\n!10\n| 12:48.64  || {{flagathlete|[[Isaiah Kiplangat Koech]] |KEN}} || 6 July 2012 || Paris || <ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n|-\n!11\n| 12:48.66  || {{flagathlete|[[Isaac Songok]] |KEN}} || 18 Aug