.net/fileadmin/html/Rankings/All_Time/5000metresmen.htm All-time Masters men's 5000 m list]\n*[http://www.mastersathletics.net/fileadmin/html/Rankings/All_Time/5000metreswomen.htm All-time Masters women's 5000 m list]\n\n{{Athletics events}}\n{{Portal bar|Athletics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5000 Metres}}\n[[Category:Events in track and field]]\n[[Category:Long-distance running distances]]\n[[Category:Summer Olympic disciplines in athletics]]\n[[Category:5000 metres| ]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:9b25:5d58:d912:6084:7ce2:bc77", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/5000_metres"}
{"title_page": "Moturoa AFC", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Moturoa AFC\n| image = \n| fullname = Moturoa Association Football and Sports Club\n| nickname = \"the Reds\"; \"Roa\"\n| founded = 1928\n| ground = Onuku Taipari Domain, [[Moturoa]], [[New Plymouth]]\n| capacity = \n| chairman = Scott Manson\n| coach = \n| league = Taranaki Premier League\n| season = 2019\n| position = 1st\n| kit_alt1 = Red shirt with white collar, shorts and socks\n| pattern_b1 = _collarwhite\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_ra1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_sh1 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so1 = _whitesides\n| leftarm1 = DD0022\n| body1 = DD0022\n| rightarm1 = DD0022\n| shorts1 = DD0022\n| socks1 = DD0022\n| kit_alt2 = Blue and white shirt, blue shorts and socks.\n| pattern_b2 = _blueshouldersandchest\n| pattern_la2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_ra2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_sh2 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so2 = _whitesides\n| leftarm2 = 0000BB\n| body2 = 0000BB\n| rightarm2 = 0000BB\n| shorts2 = 0000BB\n| socks2 = 0000BB\n| website = https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/\n}}\n\n'''Moturoa AFC''' is one of [[New Zealand]]'s oldest [[association football]] clubs. Based in [[New Plymouth]], the club traces its development back to the New Plymouth Watersiders team<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/70915|title=Watersides Soccer Team, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> from the early years of the 20th century, and has historic  links to each of the many schools from the area and greater New Plymouth.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/80812|title=Motoroa Football Team|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nThe club refers to itself as the \"Traditional home of [[Taranaki Region|Taranaki]] football\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Moturoa AFC |url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/ |website=Moturoa AFC}}</ref> Its clubrooms and home ground are at the Onuku Taipari Domain, Ngamotu Road, New Plymouth.\n\nMoturoa AFC is home to many junior sides in the Taranaki age-group grades, providing a footballing base for players from the many surrounding schools.\n\nThe club also has three men's sides and two women's sides.\n\nThough not currently playing in the upper echelons of New Zealand football, Moturoa AFC has a rich history with the club having success in many regional and national competitions.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==2019 Season==\n\nThe Taranaki Premier League team are defending Taranaki Champions and have won three successive premierships in a row, completing the 2019 season unbeaten in the league and retaining the league challenge trophy.<ref name=\"website\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth Moturoa AFC Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nThe team also hold the Sheffield United Plate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth {{!}} Moturoa AFC {{!}} Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> won in the pre-season by defeating the 2018 Central Federation Cup winners Eltham AFC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centralfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/67908|title=A Men's Federation Cup final for the ages!|website=www.centralfootball.co.nz|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Moturoa Womens Premiership team are also defending Taranaki Champions, winning the league challenge trophy along with the Central Federation Cup and Duchess Cup titles.<ref name=\"website\" />\n\n==Early History==\n\nSince the games inception in New Plymouth in 1904 there had been a steady turn over of clubs. Omata, Mangorei Swifts, Carrington and New Plymouth with rugby clubs Star and Tukapa among the original teams from Taranaki's largest town competing for the Julian Cup. In 1905 Waitara and [[Urenui]] formed teams. By 1906 New Plymouth AFC had become New Plymouth East and New Plymouth West. The New Plymouth clubs relied mainly on the port and it's visiting ships for competition. \n\nIn 1913 the New Plymouth teams comprised, The Wanderers, The Watersiders, Albion FC, Swifts and Caledonian. After the first world war many of the early clubs were never brought out of recess.\n\nOriginally Moturoa FC was a shortlived rugby club, started by the Breakwater Sports Committee in the kiosk at Ngamotu Beach in early 1914 before amalgamating with the Star club. Moturoa FC's home ground was the prison reserve field on Breakwater Road. The club retained one junior team that played in the club's colour, white, with a star emblem. \n\nNew Plymouth AFC was the first club to re-emerge in 1922 playing a well drilled Hawera at the who had played a few matches with teams from Wanganui along with the other resurgent South Taranaki clubs.\n\nThe Moturoa School opened in 1923 after years of deliberation.\n\nChina's Universities team toured New Zealand in 1924 and played a Taranaki team at Hawera. The Chinese Cup is donated to Taranaki Football.\n\nFitzroy Rangers and Pirates from eastern New Plymouth formed around 1927, both teams often played at the Bellringer Estate, home of today's Peringa United.\n\nThe Watersiders won the Duff Rose Bowl in 1927 defeating Rangers in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19270815.2.33|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Both the Watersiders and related Wanderers team dissolved after this year.  \n\nCanada toured New Zealand in 1927 and played a match against Taranaki at Pukekura Park.\n\nThe name Moturoa was first used with the Taranaki Football Association (TFA) for the 1928 season.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280611.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first TFA delegates representing Moturoa was Mr. J. McKay in 1928.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19290416.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> He had moved onto Caledonian by 1933 and in 1935 to New Plymouth Thistle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1928: In early June in the Julian Cup, Caledonian inflict a heavy 4\u20130 defeat to Moturoa.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\"/> In late August Caledonian beat Moturoa again, this time in the Duff Cup, a huge score-line of 10\u20130 recorded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280827.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By early September results improved, still playing in the Duff Cup, Moturoa beat Rangers 3\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280910.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1929: Moturoa's intermediate team, competing for the Plunket Cup, lost the final to Caledonian.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The junior championship competition was keenly contested this year with many very promising players being found in the junior ranks, the game was said to have a very bright future in Taranaki. Moturoa made up for the Plunket Cup loss by winning the Plum Cup, the Chinese Cup and the Taranaki junior championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300408.2.51|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1930: The TFA had a special meeting after receiving a letter from the New Plymouth clubs in the Northern Sub-Committee, with the Julian Cup lacking in entries. Only Stratford, Celtic (Hawera) and Albion had entered clubs. Moturoa, Caledonian, Rangers (Fitzroy) along with the club Pirates (New Plymouth) citing travel around Taranaki as detrimental to the progress of their junior competitions. A resolution was made by Mr. G.Littlejohn, that was met with approval by all the club representatives, except Rangers who had to consult their players. Moturoa's first game was scheduled for the 10th of May against Pirates,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300501.2.40|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> the result being a 5\u20131 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300512.2.14|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By the 19th of May, Rangers had dropped out for the season. Moturoa played Hawera team Celtic, losing 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300519.2.9|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>  Early June, Moturoa defaulted to Albion. Celtic, Pirates, Caledonian and Stratford managing to field teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300609.2.20|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> In early July Moturoa was drawn to play Stratford away in the first round of the Chinese Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300703.2.8|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> A match day later, Stratford became the winners of the Chinese Cup for the season beating Hawera, with Moturoa facing Caledonian in a 4\u20134 draw for the Duff Cup (Duff Rose Bowl) the same weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300714.2.21|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> The attempt to win the years Priest Shield tournament was not successful. With two teams entered (A and B), Moturoa were losing semi-finalists to Caledonian after the match ended drawn and was decided by a corner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300811.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1931: In attendance at the TFA AGM were Moturoa club delegates, F. Roper and G. Rendell. The draw was made for the Julian Cup with Moturoa playing Albion in the first round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310415.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Later in the year, Moturoa's senior team won the annual six-a-side competition for the Priest Shield at New Plymouth. There were six teams in the competition, which was conducted at Western Park. The players in the final for Moturoa were: R. Johns, R. and F. Roper, Anderson, White, Smith. And for Stratford: Grierson, Thomson, Henderson, O\u2019Shannessey, McGrory, Elgar. The final score was Moturoa 3  Stratford 1. White getting a hat-trick for Moturoa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310914.2.68|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1932: The season concluded with the annual Priest Shield contest at Western Park. Moturoa again exiting in the semi-finals, this year to Albion 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19320905.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1933: At the TFA's annual meeting in late April, held at Smith's Tea Rooms in Stratford, Waitara were accepted as an affiliated member of the association, giving further competition for Moturoa and the teams in the northern sub-committee. Albion were congratulated for winning all of the trophies in the prior season. A loan was made of \u00a35 to the northern sub-committee. Moturoa's delegates at the meeting were G.E. Roper and R.J. Page. Times had changed in South Taranaki, with the Stratford and two Hawera clubs listed as inactive. The season start date was set for May the 6th.<ref name=\":5\" /> Stratford turned this around and managed to field a team by May.<ref name=\":5\"/> The Julian Cup became a one-round competition. In all competitions except the Duff Cup, it was decided that the home team retained all the collections taken up at the match. A life sentence handed down to a player from an undisclosed club by the executive for the \"unfortunate breach of the rules of good conduct\", was reduced by the New Zealand Football Association (NZFA) to a five year suspension.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played the newly affiliated Waitara for the first time in the middle of May. The match result being a draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330515.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The week after this significant fixture the club faced Caledonian losing 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330522.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Following that match another loss, this time to Albion 6\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330529.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played Stratford, at Stratford, in June in their final Julian Cup game for the season. The game ended in a one all draw, both goals from the first half. The Moturoa team list read as follows; Thompson, Roper, Simpson, Anderson, Bensley, Johns, White, Kenny, Christensen, a second Thompson and Grey. The Julian Cup was won again by Albion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330612.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The first round of the Duff Rose Bowl saw Moturoa defeat the recent Julian Cup winners Albion, 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330626.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the second week of July the TFA suspended club football as the Taranaki representative team were travelling to Manawatu. An exhibition game of Probables v Possibles at Victoria Park used the remaining local players, with the hope of stimulating interest in the code again in South Taranaki. Moturoa's representatives scheduled to play in the fixture were, R. Kenny, R and F Roper, J. Thompson and A. Smith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330707.2.27|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nThe executive of the TFA met on the 11th of July at New Plymouth, Mr. G. E Roper from Moturoa agreed to broadcast talks on the game from local radio station 2XP. His first subject said to be \"The Organisation of Association Football in Schools\". At this time there was a considerable effort to establish the game in the schools. Stratford reporting that Tokaora and Waingongoro schools had requested balls. The executive considered the report of the referee, Mr. R. Swan, in regards to J. Thompson from Moturoa, and his sending from the field in the match against Waitara at [[Fitzroy, Taranaki|Fitzroy]] on July 1. Moturoa submitted a resolution and made representations in support, Thomson explained his view of the matter. It was decided to censure Thomson, but to take no further action as it was considered he had been sufficiently punished in being stood down from the Taranaki team that travelled to [[Manawatu District|Manawatu]] the match day prior. It was also noted in the minutes that Moturoa was to be asked to explain in \u201ccounting out\u201d the referee after a recent match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330712.2.61|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn bad weather in late July, Moturoa played Pirates in the Duff Rose Bowl. The score, unconfirmed, a possible 0\u20130 draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330724.2.4|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n1934: Moturoa defeated Stratford away. Mr. Johns, a Moturoa supporter, stepping in for the referee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330828.2.7|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa were runners up this year in the Julian Cup to winners Stratford AFC.\n\n1935: Mr. P. Gardner, who resided at Harbour Street, Moturoa, and Mr. E. Kenny were Moturoa's TFA delegates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19350417.2.45|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Gardner would later join New Plymouth Old Boys after WW2.\n\nMoturoa were one of the three New Plymouth sides in the Taranaki League for the Julian Cup in 1935, the other two being New Plymouth Albion and New Plymouth Thistle.\n\n1936: 29 June, Taranaki play Australia at Hawera. Moturoa's forward P. Gardner in the line up.\n\nIn 1938 the constitution of the club was first written.\n\n==Moturoa's Magyars==\n\nAttila Varga,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> Lotsy Varga and Lotsy Polyanszky were prominent players for the club in the late 50s and 60s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103151|title=Moturoa Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> All three players ended up being headhunted by Wellington-based [[Wellington United|Hungaria]]. Still considered by many to have been one of this country's best sides.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/105996458/hungarian-influence-remembered-as-wellington-united-marks-125th-anniversary|title=Hungarian influence remembered as Wellington United marks 125th anniversary|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nPolyanszky left Moturoa at the end of the successful 1960 season after being spotted playing for Moturoa against North Shore United in the Chatham Cup semi-final at Blandford Park. In the 1961 season Polyanszky played in the Chatham Cup final for North Shore United. And eventually became player/coach of Hungaria by 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Small Price to Pay: Refugees from Hitler in New Zealand 1986\u201346|last=Beaglehole|first=Ann|date=1988|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|isbn=9780868616353|doi = 10.7810/9780868616353}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/3897/hungaria-association-football-club-1969|title=Hungaria Association Football Club, 1969|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|website=teara.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> It has been said he was the most skillful footballer ever to grace a football field in New Zealand by many varied commentators of the game.\n\nHungaria played in the Central Region League before being invited to join the first [[New Zealand National Soccer League]] in 1970. It was the club's only season in the National League forming a composite team with Miramar Rangers as Wellington City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1524.htm|title=Wellington United|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973 Hungaria went solo again, this time in Division Two of the Central League, finishing second, to Moturoa United. Moturoa's hometown rivals Old Boys were also in Division Two in 1973.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id396.htm|title=1973|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa drew with Hungaria at home 1\u20131, and lost away in Wellington 2\u20131, the close competition between the two teams shown in the almost equal statistics.<ref name=\":4\" /> Moturoa were promoted for the 1974 season as champions. Hungaria, as runners up had to wait another year in Division Two. The two clubs crossed over in 1974 with Moturoa being relegated back to Division Two and Hungaria taking their place in Division One.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id397.htm|title=1974|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Chatham Cup==\n\nMoturoa has competed for the [[Chatham Cup]] since [[1949 Chatham Cup|1949]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/55223|title=Motorua [Moturoa], Soccer Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n1949: MAFC were beaten 6\u20131 at Western Park by [[Ohakea]].\n\n1950: The club was drawn against the multi-national [[RNZAF]] team again suffering the same fate, though this time with the more respectable result of 5-4 at Ohakea. \n\nThe club shirt colour from this time was blue and white quarters with white shorts and black socks. \n\n1951: The club goes into recess. Partially triggered from the effects of the [[1951 New Zealand waterfront dispute|waterfront dispute]] of this year on the wider [[Moturoa]] community.\n\n1953: Life member Hans Halder begins first of 25 years as MAFC President. Herb Hutton, life-member and first team player from 1945 to 1965, would resume the role of MAFC Secretary continuing until stepping down in 1972. \n\nThe club comes out of recess with a new shirt colour of red, with white shorts, and red and black hooped socks.\n\n1954: Moturoa defeat [[Wanganui]] New Settlers 1\u20130 followed by a 4\u20132 win versus Palmerston North End, drawing a home game for the North Island quarter final and being soundly defeated 3-0 by Wellington's [[Stop Out]] at Western Park.\n\n1955: [[Kiwi United]] knock Taranaki qualifiers New Plymouth Old Boys out in early August 5\u20132.\n\n1956: Moturoa win the Taranaki Championship for the first time.\n\n[[Ted Meuli]] capped NZ test cricketer and NZ Universities football representative,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Salient12061949-t1-body-d28-d9.html|title=Soccer {{!}} NZETC|website=nzetc.victoria.ac.nz|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> begins to play for the club throughout this time<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> after spending his prior years with New Plymouth rivals, Old Boys.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/60097|title=Old Boys Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n1957: An away game for Moturoa at the Sportsground against the Wanganui Settlers was lost 4\u20132. \n\n1958: Stratford AFC qualify as Taranaki preliminary winners, knocked out by Kiwi United 3\u20132 at Western Park, New Plymouth.\n\n[[1959 Chatham Cup|1959]]: Moturoa beat Stratford at Western Park 4-1, starting one of the best cup runs in the clubs history. In the next round [[Wanganui Athletic]] were beaten 3\u20131 at [[Cooks Gardens]]. In the next round Napier Athletic travelled across to New Plymouth and were beaten 6-0 at Western Park. In the quarter final at the [[Basin Reserve]] in Wellington, Moturoa were beaten by [[Miramar Rangers]] 3\u20132.\n\n1960: Moturoa win the first round 6\u20130 against Wanganui Settlers. In the next round Kiwi United were beaten 4\u20133. In the quarter final [[Brooklyn Northern United AFC|Northern]] were beaten 3-1 at Western Park.    \n\nIn the Chatham Cup semi-final Moturoa travelled to Auckland to play [[North Shore United]] at [[Blandford Park]]. The match was lost 10\u20132, one of the heaviest losses in the clubs history.    \n\nThe 1960 season is one of most successful in the clubs history. Starting with the [[Kawerau|Kawerau Town]] pre-season tournament and ending with the club representing Taranaki and bringing home the Brown Shield for the first and only time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id1653.htm|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by defeating Poverty Bay in the final of the tournament.     \n\nThe Brown Shield results from 1960 were, round one v Wanganui 6-1, round two v [[Manawatu]] 4-3, semi-final v [[Bay of Plenty]] 3-1 and the final v Poverty Bay 2-1.    \n\nThe Brown Shield winning team of 1960 consisted of the players, G. Collett, A. Varga, G. Gregory (GK), H. Hutton, M. Fugett, T. Hawley, J. Marshall (captain), L. Varga, A. Evans, L. Polyanszky, T. Verbeet and coached by C. Wells.\u00a0 \u00a0\nThe Brown Shield originated in 1892. Taranaki first challenged for the shield in 1905, playing out a 1-1 draw against holders Wellington at New Plymouth on a Thursday in late September. C. Wilson scoring for Taranaki. The team made up with players from the Omata, New Plymouth and Waitara teams. In 1906 the next challenge was also without success, losing 4-0 to Wellington in a match played at [[Eltham]] in early September. The team made up with players from South Taranaki settlements [[Auroa]], [[Kaponga]], [[Hawera]] and Eltham.     \n\n1961: Moturoa play New Plymouth City winning 4-0 at Western Park. In June, Wanganui Settlers were defeated 3-2 at the Oval in Wanganui. In July, Moturoa travelled to Napier, the match went to [[Napier Rovers]], the score unrecorded. \n\nMoturoa's midfielder John Marshall selected for the Minor Provinces team to play the visiting England XI.  \n\nOne of MAFC's best cup performances came in [[1962 Chatham Cup|1962]], with four home games at Western Park. In the Taranaki final Moturoa beat NP Old Boys 1-0. In the first round Wanganui Athletic were defeated 1-0. In the second round [[Red Sox Manawatu|St. Andrews]] were beaten 6-1. A quarter final with [[Seatoun AFC]] was won 3-1, leading to a semi-final against [[Hamilton Technical Old Boys]]. \n\nTechnical Old Boys won 4-0 in a match played before about 2000 people at [[Seddon Park]], Hamilton becoming the first North Island club outside of Auckland or Wellington to qualify for the final. Which spoke volumes for Moturoa, not only because they faced a Hamilton team with three [[List of New Zealand international footballers|New Zealand internationals]], but Technical proceeded to beat [[Otago]]\u2019s [[Northern AFC|Northern]] \u2013 who had won the [[1961 Chatham Cup|1961]] cup, 4-1 in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melvilleunited.co.nz/semifinals-celebration/|title=Semifinals celebration|website=Melville United AFC|language=en-NZ|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n1963: St. Andrews were beaten 5-2 at Western Park. At Wembley Park in the next match Wanganui United beat Moturoa 6-4.\n\nIn 1964 the club changes the playing kit colour to white shirts, red shorts and white socks. \n\nWanganui United were the opponent in round one, again at Wembley Park, a 6-2 defeat ended the cup for Moturoa.\n\nIn the [[1965 Chatham Cup|1965]] Chatham Cup, Moturoa were beaten in the 3rd round, 3-2 at [[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]]. \n\nWaitara had beaten [[Spotswood College|Spotswood]] 7-5 aet while Moturoa had beaten Old Boys 3-1 in the second round. Waitara would beat Wanganui United 3-1 in round four, and depart the competition in round five with a 2-0 loss to Napier Rovers. \n\nIn [[1966 Chatham Cup|1966]] MAFC begin wearing a full red playing kit for the first time.  \n\nIn round two of the Chatham Cup, Waitara were beaten 6-3. In round three, New Plymouth United were beaten 6-0. The next match saw the first fixture between Moturoa and [[Wairarapa United|Masterton Athletic]], a 5-2 victory. In round five Napier Rovers were beaten 4-2. In a replay of the 1959 quarter final Moturoa go out again at the hands of eventual winners of the 1966 cup. [[Miramar Rangers]] this time travelled to New Plymouth winning the tie 3-0 at Western Park. Its side featuring the country\u2019s leading goalkeeper at the time [[Peter Whiting (footballer)|Peter Whiting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miramarrangers.co.nz/club-history|title=CLUB HISTORY|website=MIRAMAR RANGERS AFC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> \n\n1967: Old Boys were beaten 3-0 in round one, New Plymouth United 6-3 in round two, in round three Napier Rovers defeat Moturoa 6-2 in Napier. \n\n1968: In round three Moturoa beat Old Boys 4-2. Round four becomes the first meeting between clubs Moturoa AFC and [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] FC. Wests winning 4-2 at New Plymouth. \n\n[[1969 Chatham Cup|1969]]: New Plymouth United are beaten 7-0. In round three Old Boys and Moturoa play out a 1 all draw. The match decided by corners and awarded to Moturoa. In round four Moturoa beat Wanganui Athletic 3-1 at Wanganui. Round five results in a 4-2 loss away to Palmerston City.\n\n1970: A 2-0 loss to Old Boys ends this years cup. \n\n1971: Round three, a 5-1 win versus NP United. In round four another drawn match against Old Boys, 1 all, won on corners by Moturoa. In round five Western Suburbs FC knock Moturoa out of the Chatham Cup 7-1 and go on to the title. \n\nThe heavy loss was avenged the next season, when Moturoa caused an upset, knocking the holders out of the cup with a fourth round 1-0 win. \n\n1972: Moturoa beat Spotswood United 8-0 in round two and Old Boys 4-1 in round three. [[Gisborne City]] were drawn at home in round five, Western League champion Moturoa failed to find the back of the net against the mid-table [[New Zealand National Soccer League|National League]] side with four goals the difference. \n\n1973: Moturoa United lose 2-0 to Old Boys in the Chatham Cup, the resources spread on a travelling Western League team, Central League team. \n\n1974: New Plymouth City were beaten 3-0 in round two. Stratford AFC were beaten 4-1 in round three. In round four Porirua United beat Moturoa 2-1 at New Plymouth.\n\n1975: Moturoa United beaten by Central City in round two of Chatham Cup. \n\n[[Sheffield United]] play a Taranaki invitation XI at [[Yarrow Stadium|Rugby Park]], New Plymouth. The Blades winning 5-0 in their second match of a three match New Zealand tour.   \n\nThe [[South Yorkshire]] team included England international [[Tony Currie (footballer)|Tony Currie]] who \"nonchalantly\" told a Daily News reporter in New Plymouth of his estimated \u00a3400,000 worth to the club and wage of \u00a310,000/year after signing in 1968 for \u00a326,000. <ref>The Daily News - Taranaki, May 30, 1975, page 10</ref> Sheffield manager [[Ken Furphy]] would later slate the Rugby Park ground saying he had offered to mow the grass himself, it being knee-deep. \n\nThe Taranaki invitation squad consisted of W. Martin (GK), R. Powell, P McCartney, D. Allman, R. Grey, K. Capewell, P. Ritchie, H. Van Heckeren, M. Johnston, W. Huntly, R. Grant. Reserves, P. Gerrard, R. White, L. Casperson, R. Paul, M. Eakins, B. Wilkinson, B. Grieg and A. Morley. \n\n1976: The formation of the Taranaki Football Company produces the composite team Taranaki United. The team would play in the Central League third division and also enter the Chatham Cup. \n\nIn round one Moturoa AFC, now independent of New Plymouth United and a partner in the Taranaki Football Company, take a heavy 6-0 loss against the Taranaki United team.\n\n1977: A round one fixture for Moturoa AFC against [[Opunake]] ends in a 2-2 stalemate. Penalties decide the tie with Opunake taking the honours 3-1.\n\n1978: 5\u20130 victories, versus Waitara in round one and over Central City in round two. Round three Taranaki United were drawn and the tie was lost 3-0.\n\n1979: First Chatham Cup match against Eltham AFC, a 4\u20132 win. In round two away fixture against Taranaki United results in a 3-2 loss.\n\nClubrooms and grounds at the Onuku Taipari Domain officially become new home for Moturoa AFC. \n\n1982: Moturoa AFC amalgamate with Spotswood AFC. \n\n1980 to 1984: Did not enter the Chatham Cup.\n\n1985: A 3-1 round one victory at home against Wanganui City. In round two Palmerton North End were drawn away, the result a 3-1 defeat.\n\n1986: Moturoa play Woodleigh Cosmos in round two at Onuku Taipari with 7-0 the score. In round three Masterton were drawn away, the result a 2-0 loss.\n\n1987: In round two Wanganui East Athletic were beaten 3-2. In round three Wellington's Stokes Valley were beaten at home in the capital with a comprehensive 3-0 victory for Moturoa AFC. In round five National League club [[Napier City Rovers]] hosted at Onuku Taipari Domain, the match resulting in a 5-1 loss for Moturoa.\n\n1988: Levin United are well beaten in round two at Moturoa 4-1. In round three the Hawkes Bay's [[Taradale, New Zealand|Taradale]] host Moturoa and win the match 3-0.\n\n1989: Massey University travel to New Plymouth and snatch a 2-1 victory ending Moturoa City's challenge.\n\n1990: Did not enter.\n\n1991: Woodleigh Cosmos were beaten 1-0 at home. [[Lower Hutt City AFC|Lower Hutt City]] from a division higher in the Central League, were drawn in round two with a 5-1 loss ending the cup for Moturoa. \n\n1992: Did not enter.\n\n1993: [[Red Sox Manawatu|Red Sox]] were played at Palmerston North in round two, the 2-1 result ending another spell competing for the Chatham Cup. Moturoa AFC would not enter again until 1999.\n\n1999: [[Wellington United]] were beaten at [[Newtown Park]] in a 4-3 round two upset. In round three [[Paraparaumu United]] visited Onuku Taipari Domain and left as winners 4-2.\n\n2000: [[Red Sox Riverside]] were destroyed 5-0 at home in round two, leading to a match with Wellington's [[Waterside Karori]]. The capital city team, third place in the Capital Premier League in 2000, were sent from the competition, a 2-1 win for Moturoa setting up a fourth round tie against [[Island Bay United]] in Wellington. After 120 minutes of play and no score the match went to penalties with Island Bay taking it 4-3.\n\n2001: [[Wainuiomata AFC|Wainuiomata]] made the trip to New Plymouth for the round two match with Moturoa winning the game 2-1. In the away fixture in round three [[Wellington Olympic]] narrowly took the game 3-2.\n\n2002: In the first Chatham Cup meeting between the two Taranaki clubs, Hawera FC were beaten 7-1 at New Plymouth. A replay from the third round of 1988 was drawn next with Moturoa again travelling to Taradale but this time returning victorious 3-1. [[Red Sox Manawatu|Manawatu]] were met in round four with the National League team handing out a 6-1 drubbing in Palmerston North.\n\n2003-2007 Did not enter\n\n2008: Round one loss versus Valeron Wanderers 2-1.\n\n2009: Byes in rounds one and two. In round three Taradale win 4-0.\n\n2010: 2015 Did not enter\n\n2016: First Chatham Cup match between Moturoa and New Plymouth Rangers results in a round two loss 2-0. \n\n==Central League==\nMoturoa was invited to join the provincial leagues in 1962 after the forming of the No.2 Central Districts League for the Elwood Cup. As Taranaki representative Moturoa won this cup in 1964. \n\nThe club formed a strong reserve team during this year and in 1965 the team won the Acheson Cup playing in the local second division.\n\nIn 1966 the Central Districts League split into a Western League and a Nelson-Manawatu league. Moturoa played in the Western League for the Pearce Cup finishing third behind Thistle (Manawatu) and Kiwi United. The decision to not compete for the Julian Cup this season marked the end of a seven year reign over the Taranaki championship beginning in 1959. The second team also played out of the province. \n\n1967: The Wanganui clubs oppose the entry of Eastern Union (Gisborne) from the Eastern League to the Western League. All other clubs withdraw from the Western League and create the two division Central Districts League. Moturoa competes in the Premier Division with Eastern Union, Manawatu Thistle, Kiwi United, Napier Rovers and St. Andrews. A second Taranaki representative, Stratford AFC finished 8th in the ten team first division. \n\nThe Taranaki-Wanganui League is won by an undefeated Moturoa who compete in both leagues, with Wanganui Athletic, Western Suburbs (Wanganui), New Plymouth United, Waitara, New Plymouth Old Boys and Wanganui United finishing in that order.\n\n1968: The first Central League begins. \n\nMoturoa has two teams in the local Taranaki division one league. Moturoa A go unbeaten and win the Julian Cup and the MBTC Cup knock-out.\n\nIn 1969 Moturoa wins the Julian Cup and entering the play-offs qualifies after the reconstruction of the Central League in 1970 along with Upper Hutt United, Napier City and Wanganui Athletic. Moturoa though does not take part, its place taken by CYFC (Wellington). The Pearce Cup for travelling reasons and expense was reduced to the Wanganui and Manawatu and Taranaki clubs weren't invited to play. This arrangement lasted until 1972.\n\n1970: New Plymouth Old Boys win promotion to Central League for 1971. Moturoa win the Duff Rose Bowl \n\n1971: Moturoa A and B are first and second in the Taranaki First Division. An undefeated Moturoa come second to Douglas Villa in the Central League playoffs. Two wins and three drawn matches against Central League teams, Wanganui City and Johnson Villa, and regional champions Brooklyn United and Napier City not giving enough points for promotion, even with a strike rate of 18 goals in 5 games.\n\nIn the 1972 pre-season Moturoa beat Wellington's [[Waterside Karori|Waterside]] in the Hilton-Petone Cup $500 knock out, 2-1 at the Camp Reserve in Waitara. [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] National League player P. Eliadis was on loan to Moturoa at his home ground at Waitara as a guest. His contract with the Lilywhites in the National League would see him flown from New Plymouth to Auckland to play. Eliadis would join Moturoa as player-coach in 1973 from Eastern Suburbs. The next round of the Hilton-Petone Cup was lost to National League club [[Gisborne City AFC|Gisborne City]] who had past Moturoa striker F. McDonald up front. \n\nFirst discussion about a Moturoa - Old Boys merger surfaces with talk in the media but amounts to nothing.\n\nMoturoa played back in the reformed Western League competition to play for the Presidents Cup. They finished top of the table with the same number of points as Kiwi United but lost on goal difference.\n\nIn a 1973 pre-season play-off Moturoa qualify for inclusion in the Central League Division Two. \n\nNew Plymouth club United and Moturoa join and establish Moturoa United, giving the club(s) a Central League and Western League team.\n\nOn 7 April 1973 the first match, an away game, in the Central League Division Two against home town rivals New Plymouth Old Boys, was played at Western Park, resulting in a 3\u20131 win for Moturoa United. Moturoa's team list for the inaugural Central League fixture: Paul Barratt, Don Harris, Ray Powell, Colin Selfe, Selwyn Brown, Peter Eliadis, Peter Wisnewski, Kevin Bussey, John Hunt, Geoff Collett, Robert Paul, Paul Brennan (sub for R. Paul).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Central League Soccer, ten year history of Central Regional Soccer League 1968-1977|last=Deverill|first=Victor, Charles|publisher=Wellington, Central Region|year=1978|isbn=|location=Puke Ariki, New Plymouth|pages=1\u2013175}}</ref>\n\nMoturoa United holds the honours of being the 1973 Central League Division Two champions<ref name=\":0\" /> gaining promotion to Division One for the 1974 season.\n\nIn 1974 New Plymouth rival clubs Central City and Old Boys began the New Plymouth City team. The team took the place of New Plymouth Old Boys in Division Two of the Central League, finishing last before relegation to Division Three for 1975. \n\nMid-season in the 1975 Moturoa United changed its name to Taranaki United. The Moturoa club chairman Mr. A. M. Hogan, players and officials from Moturoa United, City and Old Boys all agreeing to co-operate immediately to boost the provinces football standing. \n\nBoth Moturoa United and New Plymouth City, playing a division apart in the Central League changed to tangerine coloured kits for the remainder of 1975. \n\nIn 1976 the Taranaki Football Company entered into an arrangement with the other Taranaki clubs to provide their top players to a composite team [[Team Taranaki|Taranaki United]]. This agreement lasted until 1982 when the New Plymouth Old Boys club bought the Taranaki United identity and its position in the Central League as a limited company. Central City left the arrangement in 1983 taking the New Plymouth City name with them. The name Taranaki United was used until the end of the 1984 season, the team relegated from the first division with Porirua Viard Old Boys to the second division. From 1985 the team was solely called New Plymouth Old Boys.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1430.htm|title=Moturoa|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nUnder T. Brady, who had left the Hawera football club for the coaching role, Moturoa were promoted back to the Central League as Western League champions in 1985, winning also the City of New Plymouth tournament and the Duff Rose Bowl. \n\nMoturoa entered the Central League Third Division in 1986 and finished sixth, with home town rivals Central City playing as New Plymouth City, finishing 10th.\n\nIn 1987 Moturoa finished third. New Plymouth City won promotion behind Wainuiomata AFC to the second division.\n\nIn 1988 Moturoa finished ninth from eleven teams with Port Hill United and Takaro AFC beneath the club on the ladder. In the second division New Plymouth City also finished ninth.\n\nIn 1989 Moturoa and Central City<ref name=\"Central City\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1457.htm|title=Central City|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> formed a composite first team in the Central League called Moturoa/NP City. Moturoa relinquished the third division position with the new team taking the second division position held by City. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Central City\" /> \n\nThe playing strip in 1989 mixed the colours of both clubs, with the Pony branded shirt in red with gold shoulders, trim and numbering, and the main sponsor, the Ngamotu Tavern across the chest in white.\n\nChatham Cup winner with [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs FC]] in 1971, John Connor was assigned the head coaching role. Three players were brought in for the 1989 season, Englishmen [[Russell Irving]] and Darren Fletcher along with New Zealand under 16 midfielder Karl Cherrie. The team won promotion to Division One as runners up to winners [[Havelock North Wanderers]]. Moturoa City had the best defence in the entire three divisions of the Central League in 1989 with only 16 goals conceded in 22 matches while scoring 42.\n\nIn 1990 executive distractions off the pitch, travelling pressures, including an away match in the South Island, along with significant changes in the squad and the failure of the two clubs to agree on the conditions of a proposed amalgamation saw the team relegated back to the second division.\n\nMoturoa independently retained the position in Division Two of the Central League from 1991.  \n\nIn 1992 the creation of the Central Premier League restructured the divisions. Moturoa compete in Division One and finish mid-table.\n\nNew Plymouth City moved into Marfell Park after the ground and clubroom became available following the amalgamation of Star RFC and Spotswood Old Boys RFC remaining at the ground and climbing through the Central League until 1998 when the club, re-named Mt. Taranaki for its final year, were dissolved and the grounds and clubroom abandoned and eventually demolished.\n\nIn 1993, coached by Angus Livingstone, Moturoa won promotion to the Central Premier League as runners up to Stokes Valley. The acquisition of Stephen Douglas from Belfast's [[Glentoran FC]] and fellow Northern Irish countryman Tony Jones assisting the push for honours. Jones would later transfer to Napier City Rovers with Douglas returning to Europe.\n\n1994 saw Moturoa finish at the foot of the ladder in the Premier League and a decision was made by the President J. Seed to withdraw from the Central League and return the focus of the club to local football.  \n\nThere was talk in the air and media around this time of a merger between Woodleigh Cosmos and Moturoa, with the clubs already co-operating in the prior two seasons with composite ladies and youth teams. Both clubs remained independent with the reports amounting to nothing.  \n\nAfter this season the club did not play in the Central League again until 2000 when it once again competed for the Central Federation Premier League, having its final season to date at this level in 2003.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Taranaki Premier League Squad 2019==\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|pos=GK|nat=New Zealand         |name=Zane Coleman|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= |pos=  |nat=|name=|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Ethan Webber|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Corbin Richardson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Liam Scott|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Nathan Morath|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Jaden Taylor|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Troy Jury|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Hayden Murray|other=Captain}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= |other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=11 |pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= Tyler Paterson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|pos=  |nat=New Zealand        |name= Ash Reader-Nokes|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Scott Manson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Jacob Crawford|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Zayed Rabbaney|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Sutton|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Westlake|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Nicholas Parthemore|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Dean Wilson|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kayi Erol-Watt|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kobi Hislop|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Moturoa AFC players|Moturoa AFC players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sport in New Plymouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Moturoa AFC\n| image = \n| fullname = Moturoa Association Football and Sports Club\n| nickname = \"the Reds\"; \"Roa\"\n| founded = 1928\n| ground = Onuku Taipari Domain, [[Moturoa]], [[New Plymouth]]\n| capacity = \n| chairman = Scott Manson\n| coach = \n| league = Taranaki Premier League\n| season = 2019\n| position = 1st\n| kit_alt1 = Red shirt with white collar, shorts and socks\n| pattern_b1 = _collarwhite\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_ra1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_sh1 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so1 = _whitesides\n| leftarm1 = DD0022\n| body1 = DD0022\n| rightarm1 = DD0022\n| shorts1 = DD0022\n| socks1 = DD0022\n| kit_alt2 = Blue and white shirt, blue shorts and socks.\n| pattern_b2 = _blueshouldersandchest\n| pattern_la2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_ra2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_sh2 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so2 = _whitesides\n| leftarm2 = 0000BB\n| body2 = 0000BB\n| rightarm2 = 0000BB\n| shorts2 = 0000BB\n| socks2 = 0000BB\n| website = https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/\n}}\n\n'''Moturoa AFC''' is one of [[New Zealand]]'s oldest [[association football]] clubs. Based in [[New Plymouth]], the club traces its development back to the New Plymouth Watersiders team<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/70915|title=Watersides Soccer Team, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> from the early years of the 20th century, and has historic  links to each of the many schools from the area and greater New Plymouth.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/80812|title=Motoroa Football Team|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nThe club refers to itself as the \"Traditional home of [[Taranaki Region|Taranaki]] football\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Moturoa AFC |url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/ |website=Moturoa AFC}}</ref> Its clubrooms and home ground are at the Onuku Taipari Domain, Ngamotu Road, New Plymouth.\n\nMoturoa AFC is home to many junior sides in the Taranaki age-group grades, providing a footballing base for players from the many surrounding schools.\n\nThe club also has three men's sides and two women's sides.\n\nThough not currently playing in the upper echelons of New Zealand football, Moturoa AFC has a rich history with the club having success in many regional and national competitions.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==2019 Season==\n\nThe Taranaki Premier League team are defending Taranaki Champions and have won three successive premierships in a row, completing the 2019 season unbeaten in the league and retaining the league challenge trophy.<ref name=\"website\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth Moturoa AFC Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nThe team also hold the Sheffield United Plate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth {{!}} Moturoa AFC {{!}} Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> won in the pre-season by defeating the 2018 Central Federation Cup winners Eltham AFC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centralfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/67908|title=A Men's Federation Cup final for the ages!|website=www.centralfootball.co.nz|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Moturoa Womens Premiership team are also defending Taranaki Champions, winning the league challenge trophy along with the Central Federation Cup and Duchess Cup titles.<ref name=\"website\" />\n\n==Early History==\n\nSince the games inception in New Plymouth in 1904 there had been a steady turn over of clubs. Omata, Mangorei Swifts, Carrington and New Plymouth with rugby clubs Star and Tukapa among the original teams from Taranaki's largest town competing for the Julian Cup. In 1905 Waitara and [[Urenui]] formed teams. By 1906 New Plymouth AFC had become New Plymouth East and New Plymouth West. The New Plymouth clubs relied mainly on the port and it's visiting ships for competition. \n\nIn 1913 the New Plymouth teams comprised, The Wanderers, The Watersiders, Albion FC, Swifts and Caledonian. After the first world war many of the early clubs were never brought out of recess.\n\nOriginally Moturoa FC was a shortlived rugby club, started by the Breakwater Sports Committee in the kiosk at Ngamotu Beach in early 1914 before amalgamating with the Star club. Moturoa FC's home ground was the prison reserve field on Breakwater Road. The club retained one junior team that played in the club's colour, white, with a star emblem. \n\nNew Plymouth AFC was the first club to re-emerge in 1922 playing a well drilled Hawera at the who had played a few matches with teams from Wanganui along with the other resurgent South Taranaki clubs.\n\nThe Moturoa School opened in 1923 after years of deliberation.\n\nChina's Universities team toured New Zealand in 1924 and played a Taranaki team at Hawera. The Chinese Cup is donated to Taranaki Football.\n\nFitzroy Rangers and Pirates from eastern New Plymouth formed around 1927, both teams often played at the Bellringer Estate, home of today's Peringa United.\n\nThe Watersiders won the Duff Rose Bowl in 1927 defeating Rangers in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19270815.2.33|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Both the Watersiders and related Wanderers team dissolved after this year.  \n\nCanada toured New Zealand in 1927 and played a match against Taranaki at Pukekura Park.\n\nThe name Moturoa was first used with the Taranaki Football Association (TFA) for the 1928 season.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280611.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first TFA delegates representing Moturoa was Mr. J. McKay in 1928.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19290416.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> He had moved onto Caledonian by 1933 and in 1935 to New Plymouth Thistle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1928: In early June in the Julian Cup, Caledonian inflict a heavy 4\u20130 defeat to Moturoa.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\"/> In late August Caledonian beat Moturoa again, this time in the Duff Cup, a huge score-line of 10\u20130 recorded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280827.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By early September results improved, still playing in the Duff Cup, Moturoa beat Rangers 3\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280910.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1929: Moturoa's intermediate team, competing for the Plunket Cup, lost the final to Caledonian.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The junior championship competition was keenly contested this year with many very promising players being found in the junior ranks, the game was said to have a very bright future in Taranaki. Moturoa made up for the Plunket Cup loss by winning the Plum Cup, the Chinese Cup and the Taranaki junior championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300408.2.51|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1930: The TFA had a special meeting after receiving a letter from the New Plymouth clubs in the Northern Sub-Committee, with the Julian Cup lacking in entries. Only Stratford, Celtic (Hawera) and Albion had entered clubs. Moturoa, Caledonian, Rangers (Fitzroy) along with the club Pirates (New Plymouth) citing travel around Taranaki as detrimental to the progress of their junior competitions. A resolution was made by Mr. G.Littlejohn, that was met with approval by all the club representatives, except Rangers who had to consult their players. Moturoa's first game was scheduled for the 10th of May against Pirates,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300501.2.40|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> the result being a 5\u20131 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300512.2.14|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By the 19th of May, Rangers had dropped out for the season. Moturoa played Hawera team Celtic, losing 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300519.2.9|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>  Early June, Moturoa defaulted to Albion. Celtic, Pirates, Caledonian and Stratford managing to field teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300609.2.20|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> In early July Moturoa was drawn to play Stratford away in the first round of the Chinese Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300703.2.8|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> A match day later, Stratford became the winners of the Chinese Cup for the season beating Hawera, with Moturoa facing Caledonian in a 4\u20134 draw for the Duff Cup (Duff Rose Bowl) the same weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300714.2.21|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> The attempt to win the years Priest Shield tournament was not successful. With two teams entered (A and B), Moturoa were losing semi-finalists to Caledonian after the match ended drawn and was decided by a corner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300811.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1931: In attendance at the TFA AGM were Moturoa club delegates, F. Roper and G. Rendell. The draw was made for the Julian Cup with Moturoa playing Albion in the first round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310415.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Later in the year, Moturoa's senior team won the annual six-a-side competition for the Priest Shield at New Plymouth. There were six teams in the competition, which was conducted at Western Park. The players in the final for Moturoa were: R. Johns, R. and F. Roper, Anderson, White, Smith. And for Stratford: Grierson, Thomson, Henderson, O\u2019Shannessey, McGrory, Elgar. The final score was Moturoa 3  Stratford 1. White getting a hat-trick for Moturoa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310914.2.68|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1932: The season concluded with the annual Priest Shield contest at Western Park. Moturoa again exiting in the semi-finals, this year to Albion 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19320905.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1933: At the TFA's annual meeting in late April, held at Smith's Tea Rooms in Stratford, Waitara were accepted as an affiliated member of the association, giving further competition for Moturoa and the teams in the northern sub-committee. Albion were congratulated for winning all of the trophies in the prior season. A loan was made of \u00a35 to the northern sub-committee. Moturoa's delegates at the meeting were G.E. Roper and R.J. Page. Times had changed in South Taranaki, with the Stratford and two Hawera clubs listed as inactive. The season start date was set for May the 6th.<ref name=\":5\" /> Stratford turned this around and managed to field a team by May.<ref name=\":5\"/> The Julian Cup became a one-round competition. In all competitions except the Duff Cup, it was decided that the home team retained all the collections taken up at the match. A life sentence handed down to a player from an undisclosed club by the executive for the \"unfortunate breach of the rules of good conduct\", was reduced by the New Zealand Football Association (NZFA) to a five year suspension.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played the newly affiliated Waitara for the first time in the middle of May. The match result being a draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330515.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The week after this significant fixture the club faced Caledonian losing 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330522.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Following that match another loss, this time to Albion 6\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330529.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played Stratford, at Stratford, in June in their final Julian Cup game for the season. The game ended in a one all draw, both goals from the first half. The Moturoa team list read as follows; Thompson, Roper, Simpson, Anderson, Bensley, Johns, White, Kenny, Christensen, a second Thompson and Grey. The Julian Cup was won again by Albion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330612.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The first round of the Duff Rose Bowl saw Moturoa defeat the recent Julian Cup winners Albion, 2\u20131.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330626.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the second week of July the TFA suspended club football as the Taranaki representative team were travelling to Manawatu. An exhibition game of Probables v Possibles at Victoria Park used the remaining local players, with the hope of stimulating interest in the code again in South Taranaki. Moturoa's representatives scheduled to play in the fixture were, R. Kenny, R and F Roper, J. Thompson and A. Smith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330707.2.27|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nThe executive of the TFA met on the 11th of July at New Plymouth, Mr. G. E Roper from Moturoa agreed to broadcast talks on the game from local radio station 2XP. His first subject said to be \"The Organisation of Association Football in Schools\". At this time there was a considerable effort to establish the game in the schools. Stratford reporting that Tokaora and Waingongoro schools had requested balls. The executive considered the report of the referee, Mr. R. Swan, in regards to J. Thompson from Moturoa, and his sending from the field in the match against Waitara at [[Fitzroy, Taranaki|Fitzroy]] on July 1. Moturoa submitted a resolution and made representations in support, Thomson explained his view of the matter. It was decided to censure Thomson, but to take no further action as it was considered he had been sufficiently punished in being stood down from the Taranaki team that travelled to [[Manawatu District|Manawatu]] the match day prior. It was also noted in the minutes that Moturoa was to be asked to explain in \u201ccounting out\u201d the referee after a recent match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330712.2.61|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn bad weather in late July, Moturoa played Pirates in the Duff Rose Bowl. The score, unconfirmed, a possible 0\u20130 draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330724.2.4|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n1934: Moturoa defeated Stratford away. Mr. Johns, a Moturoa supporter, stepping in for the referee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330828.2.7|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa were runners up this year in the Julian Cup to winners Stratford AFC.\n\n1935: Mr. P. Gardner, who resided at Harbour Street, Moturoa, and Mr. E. Kenny were Moturoa's TFA delegates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19350417.2.45|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Gardner would later join New Plymouth Old Boys after WW2.\n\nMoturoa were one of the three New Plymouth sides in the Taranaki League for the Julian Cup in 1935, the other two being New Plymouth Albion and New Plymouth Thistle.\n\n1936: 29 June, Taranaki play Australia at Hawera. Moturoa's forward P. Gardner in the line up.\n\nIn 1938 the constitution of the club was first written.\n\n==Moturoa's Magyars==\n\nAttila Varga,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> Lotsy Varga and Lotsy Polyanszky were prominent players for the club in the late 50s and 60s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103151|title=Moturoa Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> All three players ended up being headhunted by Wellington-based [[Wellington United|Hungaria]]. Still considered by many to have been one of this country's best sides.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/105996458/hungarian-influence-remembered-as-wellington-united-marks-125th-anniversary|title=Hungarian influence remembered as Wellington United marks 125th anniversary|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nPolyanszky left Moturoa at the end of the successful 1960 season after being spotted playing for Moturoa against North Shore United in the Chatham Cup semi-final at Blandford Park. In the 1961 season Polyanszky played in the Chatham Cup final for North Shore United. And eventually became player/coach of Hungaria by 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Small Price to Pay: Refugees from Hitler in New Zealand 1986\u201346|last=Beaglehole|first=Ann|date=1988|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|isbn=9780868616353|doi = 10.7810/9780868616353}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/3897/hungaria-association-football-club-1969|title=Hungaria Association Football Club, 1969|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|website=teara.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> It has been said he was the most skillful footballer ever to grace a football field in New Zealand by many varied commentators of the game.\n\nHungaria played in the Central Region League before being invited to join the first [[New Zealand National Soccer League]] in 1970. It was the club's only season in the National League forming a composite team with Miramar Rangers as Wellington City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1524.htm|title=Wellington United|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973 Hungaria went solo again, this time in Division Two of the Central League, finishing second, to Moturoa United. Moturoa's hometown rivals Old Boys were also in Division Two in 1973.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id396.htm|title=1973|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa drew with Hungaria at home 1\u20131, and lost away in Wellington 2\u20131, the close competition between the two teams shown in the almost equal statistics.<ref name=\":4\" /> Moturoa were promoted for the 1974 season as champions. Hungaria, as runners up had to wait another year in Division Two. The two clubs crossed over in 1974 with Moturoa being relegated back to Division Two and Hungaria taking their place in Division One.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id397.htm|title=1974|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Chatham Cup==\n\nMoturoa has competed for the [[Chatham Cup]] since [[1949 Chatham Cup|1949]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/55223|title=Motorua [Moturoa], Soccer Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n1949: MAFC were beaten 6\u20131 at Western Park by [[Ohakea]].\n\n1950: The club was drawn against the multi-national [[RNZAF]] team again suffering the same fate, though this time with the more respectable result of 5-4 at Ohakea. \n\nThe club shirt colour from this time was blue and white quarters with white shorts and black socks. \n\n1951: The club goes into recess. Partially triggered from the effects of the [[1951 New Zealand waterfront dispute|waterfront dispute]] of this year on the wider [[Moturoa]] community.\n\n1953: Life member Hans Halder begins first of 25 years as MAFC President. Herb Hutton, life-member and first team player from 1945 to 1965, would resume the role of MAFC Secretary continuing until stepping down in 1972. \n\nThe club comes out of recess with a new shirt colour of red, with white shorts, and red and black hooped socks.\n\n1954: Moturoa defeat [[Wanganui]] New Settlers 1\u20130 followed by a 4\u20132 win versus Palmerston North End, drawing a home game for the North Island quarter final and being soundly defeated 3-0 by Wellington's [[Stop Out]] at Western Park.\n\n1955: [[Kiwi United]] knock Taranaki qualifiers New Plymouth Old Boys out in early August 5\u20132.\n\n1956: Moturoa win the Taranaki Championship for the first time.\n\n[[Ted Meuli]] capped NZ test cricketer and NZ Universities football representative,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Salient12061949-t1-body-d28-d9.html|title=Soccer {{!}} NZETC|website=nzetc.victoria.ac.nz|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> begins to play for the club throughout this time<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> after spending his prior years with New Plymouth rivals, Old Boys.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/60097|title=Old Boys Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n1957: An away game for Moturoa at the Sportsground against the Wanganui Settlers was lost 4\u20132. \n\n1958: Stratford AFC qualify as Taranaki preliminary winners, knocked out by Kiwi United 3\u20132 at Western Park, New Plymouth.\n\n[[1959 Chatham Cup|1959]]: Moturoa beat Stratford at Western Park 4-1, starting one of the best cup runs in the clubs history. In the next round [[Wanganui Athletic]] were beaten 3\u20131 at [[Cooks Gardens]]. In the next round Napier Athletic travelled across to New Plymouth and were beaten 6-0 at Western Park. In the quarter final at the [[Basin Reserve]] in Wellington, Moturoa were beaten by [[Miramar Rangers]] 3\u20132.\n\n1960: Moturoa win the first round 6\u20130 against Wanganui Settlers. In the next round Kiwi United were beaten 4\u20133. In the quarter final [[Brooklyn Northern United AFC|Northern]] were beaten 3-1 at Western Park.    \n\nIn the Chatham Cup semi-final Moturoa travelled to Auckland to play [[North Shore United]] at [[Blandford Park]]. The match was lost 10\u20132, one of the heaviest losses in the clubs history.    \n\nThe 1960 season is one of most successful in the clubs history. Starting with the [[Kawerau|Kawerau Town]] pre-season tournament and ending with the club representing Taranaki and bringing home the Brown Shield for the first and only time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id1653.htm|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by defeating Poverty Bay in the final of the tournament.     \n\nThe Brown Shield results from 1960 were, round one v Wanganui 6-1, round two v [[Manawatu]] 4-3, semi-final v [[Bay of Plenty]] 3-1 and the final v Poverty Bay 2-1.    \n\nThe Brown Shield winning team of 1960 consisted of the players, G. Collett, A. Varga, G. Gregory (GK), H. Hutton, M. Fugett, T. Hawley, J. Marshall (captain), L. Varga, A. Evans, L. Polyanszky, T. Verbeet and coached by C. Wells.\u00a0 \u00a0\nThe Brown Shield originated in 1892. Taranaki first challenged for the shield in 1905, playing out a 1-1 draw against holders Wellington at New Plymouth on a Thursday in late September. C. Wilson scoring for Taranaki. The team made up with players from the Omata, New Plymouth and Waitara teams. In 1906 the next challenge was also without success, losing 4-0 to Wellington in a match played at [[Eltham]] in early September. The team made up with players from South Taranaki settlements [[Auroa]], [[Kaponga]], [[Hawera]] and Eltham.     \n\n1961: Moturoa play New Plymouth City winning 4-0 at Western Park. In June, Wanganui Settlers were defeated 3-2 at the Oval in Wanganui. In July, Moturoa travelled to Napier, the match went to [[Napier Rovers]], the score unrecorded. \n\nMoturoa's midfielder John Marshall selected for the Minor Provinces team to play the visiting England XI.  \n\nOne of MAFC's best cup performances came in [[1962 Chatham Cup|1962]], with four home games at Western Park. In the Taranaki final Moturoa beat NP Old Boys 1-0. In the first round Wanganui Athletic were defeated 1-0. In the second round [[Red Sox Manawatu|St. Andrews]] were beaten 6-1. A quarter final with [[Seatoun AFC]] was won 3-1, leading to a semi-final against [[Hamilton Technical Old Boys]]. \n\nTechnical Old Boys won 4-0 in a match played before about 2000 people at [[Seddon Park]], Hamilton becoming the first North Island club outside of Auckland or Wellington to qualify for the final. Which spoke volumes for Moturoa, not only because they faced a Hamilton team with three [[List of New Zealand international footballers|New Zealand internationals]], but Technical proceeded to beat [[Otago]]\u2019s [[Northern AFC|Northern]] \u2013 who had won the [[1961 Chatham Cup|1961]] cup, 4-1 in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melvilleunited.co.nz/semifinals-celebration/|title=Semifinals celebration|website=Melville United AFC|language=en-NZ|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n1963: St. Andrews were beaten 5-2 at Western Park. At Wembley Park in the next match Wanganui United beat Moturoa 6-4.\n\nIn 1964 the club changes the playing kit colour to white shirts, red shorts and white socks. \n\nWanganui United were the opponent in round one, again at Wembley Park, a 6-2 defeat ended the cup for Moturoa.\n\nIn the [[1965 Chatham Cup|1965]] Chatham Cup, Moturoa were beaten in the 3rd round, 3-2 at [[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]]. \n\nWaitara had beaten [[Spotswood College|Spotswood]] 7-5 aet while Moturoa had beaten Old Boys 3-1 in the second round. Waitara would beat Wanganui United 3-1 in round four, and depart the competition in round five with a 2-0 loss to Napier Rovers. \n\nIn [[1966 Chatham Cup|1966]] MAFC begin wearing a full red playing kit for the first time.  \n\nIn round two of the Chatham Cup, Waitara were beaten 6-3. In round three, New Plymouth United were beaten 6-0. The next match saw the first fixture between Moturoa and [[Wairarapa United|Masterton Athletic]], a 5-2 victory. In round five Napier Rovers were beaten 4-2. In a replay of the 1959 quarter final Moturoa go out again at the hands of eventual winners of the 1966 cup. [[Miramar Rangers]] this time travelled to New Plymouth winning the tie 3-0 at Western Park. Its side featuring the country\u2019s leading goalkeeper at the time [[Peter Whiting (footballer)|Peter Whiting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miramarrangers.co.nz/club-history|title=CLUB HISTORY|website=MIRAMAR RANGERS AFC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> \n\n1967: Old Boys were beaten 3-0 in round one, New Plymouth United 6-3 in round two, in round three Napier Rovers defeat Moturoa 6-2 in Napier. \n\n1968: In round three Moturoa beat Old Boys 4-2. Round four becomes the first meeting between clubs Moturoa AFC and [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] FC. Wests winning 4-2 at New Plymouth. \n\n[[1969 Chatham Cup|1969]]: New Plymouth United are beaten 7-0. In round three Old Boys and Moturoa play out a 1 all draw. The match decided by corners and awarded to Moturoa. In round four Moturoa beat Wanganui Athletic 3-1 at Wanganui. Round five results in a 4-2 loss away to Palmerston City.\n\n1970: A 2-0 loss to Old Boys ends this years cup. \n\n1971: Round three, a 5-1 win versus NP United. In round four another drawn match against Old Boys, 1 all, won on corners by Moturoa. In round five Western Suburbs FC knock Moturoa out of the Chatham Cup 7-1 and go on to the title. \n\nThe heavy loss was avenged the next season, when Moturoa caused an upset, knocking the holders out of the cup with a fourth round 1-0 win. \n\n1972: Moturoa beat Spotswood United 8-0 in round two and Old Boys 4-1 in round three. [[Gisborne City]] were drawn at home in round five, Western League champion Moturoa failed to find the back of the net against the mid-table [[New Zealand National Soccer League|National League]] side with four goals the difference. \n\n1973: Moturoa United lose 2-0 to Old Boys in the Chatham Cup, the resources spread on a travelling Western League team, Central League team. \n\n1974: New Plymouth City were beaten 3-0 in round two. Stratford AFC were beaten 4-1 in round three. In round four Porirua United beat Moturoa 2-1 at New Plymouth.\n\n1975: Moturoa United beaten by Central City in round two of Chatham Cup. \n\n[[Sheffield United]] play a Taranaki invitation XI at [[Yarrow Stadium|Rugby Park]], New Plymouth. The Blades winning 5-0 in their second match of a three match New Zealand tour.   \n\nThe [[South Yorkshire]] team included England international [[Tony Currie (footballer)|Tony Currie]] who \"nonchalantly\" told a Daily News reporter in New Plymouth of his estimated \u00a3400,000 worth to the club and wage of \u00a310,000/year after signing in 1968 for \u00a326,000. <ref>The Daily News - Taranaki, May 30, 1975, page 10</ref> Sheffield manager [[Ken Furphy]] would later slate the Rugby Park ground saying he had offered to mow the grass himself, it being knee-deep. \n\nThe Taranaki invitation squad consisted of W. Martin (GK), R. Powell, P McCartney, D. Allman, R. Grey, K. Capewell, P. Ritchie, H. Van Heckeren, M. Johnston, W. Huntly, R. Grant. Reserves, P. Gerrard, R. White, L. Casperson, R. Paul, M. Eakins, B. Wilkinson, B. Grieg and A. Morley. \n\n1976: The formation of the Taranaki Football Company produces the composite team Taranaki United. The team would play in the Central League third division and also enter the Chatham Cup. \n\nIn round one Moturoa AFC, now independent of New Plymouth United and a partner in the Taranaki Football Company, take a heavy 6-0 loss against the Taranaki United team.\n\n1977: A round one fixture for Moturoa AFC against [[Opunake]] ends in a 2-2 stalemate. Penalties decide the tie with Opunake taking the honours 3-1.\n\n1978: 5\u20130 victories, versus Waitara in round one and over Central City in round two. Round three Taranaki United were drawn and the tie was lost 3-0.\n\n1979: First Chatham Cup match against Eltham AFC, a 4\u20132 win. In round two away fixture against Taranaki United results in a 3-2 loss.\n\nClubrooms and grounds at the Onuku Taipari Domain officially become new home for Moturoa AFC. \n\n1982: Moturoa AFC amalgamate with Spotswood AFC. \n\n1980 to 1984: Did not enter the Chatham Cup.\n\n1985: A 3-1 round one victory at home against Wanganui City. In round two Palmerton North End were drawn away, the result a 3-1 defeat.\n\n1986: Moturoa play Woodleigh Cosmos in round two at Onuku Taipari with 7-0 the score. In round three Masterton were drawn away, the result a 2-0 loss.\n\n1987: In round two Wanganui East Athletic were beaten 3-2. In round three Wellington's Stokes Valley were beaten at home in the capital with a comprehensive 3-0 victory for Moturoa AFC. In round five National League club [[Napier City Rovers]] hosted at Onuku Taipari Domain, the match resulting in a 5-1 loss for Moturoa.\n\n1988: Levin United are well beaten in round two at Moturoa 4-1. In round three the Hawkes Bay's [[Taradale, New Zealand|Taradale]] host Moturoa and win the match 3-0.\n\n1989: Massey University travel to New Plymouth and snatch a 2-1 victory ending Moturoa City's challenge.\n\n1990: Did not enter.\n\n1991: Woodleigh Cosmos were beaten 1-0 at home. [[Lower Hutt City AFC|Lower Hutt City]] from a division higher in the Central League, were drawn in round two with a 5-1 loss ending the cup for Moturoa. \n\n1992: Did not enter.\n\n1993: [[Red Sox Manawatu|Red Sox]] were played at Palmerston North in round two, the 2-1 result ending another spell competing for the Chatham Cup. Moturoa AFC would not enter again until 1999.\n\n1999: [[Wellington United]] were beaten at [[Newtown Park]] in a 4-3 round two upset. In round three [[Paraparaumu United]] visited Onuku Taipari Domain and left as winners 4-2.\n\n2000: [[Red Sox Riverside]] were destroyed 5-0 at home in round two, leading to a match with Wellington's [[Waterside Karori]]. The capital city team, third place in the Capital Premier League in 2000, were sent from the competition, a 2-1 win for Moturoa setting up a fourth round tie against [[Island Bay United]] in Wellington. After 120 minutes of play and no score the match went to penalties with Island Bay taking it 4-3.\n\n2001: [[Wainuiomata AFC|Wainuiomata]] made the trip to New Plymouth for the round two match with Moturoa winning the game 2-1. In the away fixture in round three [[Wellington Olympic]] narrowly took the game 3-2.\n\n2002: In the first Chatham Cup meeting between the two Taranaki clubs, Hawera FC were beaten 7-1 at New Plymouth. A replay from the third round of 1988 was drawn next with Moturoa again travelling to Taradale but this time returning victorious 3-1. [[Red Sox Manawatu|Manawatu]] were met in round four with the National League team handing out a 6-1 drubbing in Palmerston North.\n\n2003-2007 Did not enter\n\n2008: Round one loss versus Valeron Wanderers 2-1.\n\n2009: Byes in rounds one and two. In round three Taradale win 4-0.\n\n2010: 2015 Did not enter\n\n2016: First Chatham Cup match between Moturoa and New Plymouth Rangers results in a round two loss 2-0. \n\n==Central League==\nMoturoa was invited to join the provincial leagues in 1962 after the forming of the No.2 Central Districts League for the Elwood Cup. As Taranaki representative Moturoa won this cup in 1964. \n\nThe club formed a strong reserve team during this year and in 1965 the team won the Acheson Cup playing in the local second division.\n\nIn 1966 the Central Districts League split into a Western League and a Nelson-Manawatu league. Moturoa played in the Western League for the Pearce Cup finishing third behind Thistle (Manawatu) and Kiwi United. The decision to not compete for the Julian Cup this season marked the end of a seven year reign over the Taranaki championship beginning in 1959. The second team also played out of the province. \n\n1967: The Wanganui clubs oppose the entry of Eastern Union (Gisborne) from the Eastern League to the Western League. All other clubs withdraw from the Western League and create the two division Central Districts League. Moturoa competes in the Premier Division with Eastern Union, Manawatu Thistle, Kiwi United, Napier Rovers and St. Andrews. A second Taranaki representative, Stratford AFC finished 8th in the ten team first division. \n\nThe Taranaki-Wanganui League is won by an undefeated Moturoa who compete in both leagues, with Wanganui Athletic, Western Suburbs (Wanganui), New Plymouth United, Waitara, New Plymouth Old Boys and Wanganui United finishing in that order.\n\n1968: The first Central League begins. \n\nMoturoa has two teams in the local Taranaki division one league. Moturoa A go unbeaten and win the Julian Cup and the MBTC Cup knock-out.\n\nIn 1969 Moturoa wins the Julian Cup and entering the play-offs qualifies after the reconstruction of the Central League in 1970 along with Upper Hutt United, Napier City and Wanganui Athletic. Moturoa though does not take part, its place taken by CYFC (Wellington). The Pearce Cup for travelling reasons and expense was reduced to the Wanganui and Manawatu and Taranaki clubs weren't invited to play. This arrangement lasted until 1972.\n\n1970: New Plymouth Old Boys win promotion to Central League for 1971. Moturoa win the Duff Rose Bowl \n\n1971: Moturoa A and B are first and second in the Taranaki First Division. An undefeated Moturoa come second to Douglas Villa in the Central League playoffs. Two wins and three drawn matches against Central League teams, Wanganui City and Johnson Villa, and regional champions Brooklyn United and Napier City not giving enough points for promotion, even with a strike rate of 18 goals in 5 games.\n\nIn the 1972 pre-season Moturoa beat Wellington's [[Waterside Karori|Waterside]] in the Hilton-Petone Cup $500 knock out, 2-1 at the Camp Reserve in Waitara. [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] National League player P. Eliadis was on loan to Moturoa at his home ground at Waitara as a guest. His contract with the Lilywhites in the National League would see him flown from New Plymouth to Auckland to play. Eliadis would join Moturoa as player-coach in 1973 from Eastern Suburbs. The next round of the Hilton-Petone Cup was lost to National League club [[Gisborne City AFC|Gisborne City]] who had past Moturoa striker F. McDonald up front. \n\nFirst discussion about a Moturoa - Old Boys merger surfaces with talk in the media but amounts to nothing.\n\nMoturoa played back in the reformed Western League competition to play for the Presidents Cup. They finished top of the table with the same number of points as Kiwi United but lost on goal difference.\n\nIn a 1973 pre-season play-off Moturoa qualify for inclusion in the Central League Division Two. \n\nNew Plymouth club United and Moturoa join and establish Moturoa United, giving the club(s) a Central League and Western League team.\n\nOn 7 April 1973 the first match, an away game, in the Central League Division Two against home town rivals New Plymouth Old Boys, was played at Western Park, resulting in a 3\u20131 win for Moturoa United. Moturoa's team list for the inaugural Central League fixture: Paul Barratt, Don Harris, Ray Powell, Colin Selfe, Selwyn Brown, Peter Eliadis, Peter Wisnewski, Kevin Bussey, John Hunt, Geoff Collett, Robert Paul, Paul Brennan (sub for R. Paul).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Central League Soccer, ten year history of Central Regional Soccer League 1968-1977|last=Deverill|first=Victor, Charles|publisher=Wellington, Central Region|year=1978|isbn=|location=Puke Ariki, New Plymouth|pages=1\u2013175}}</ref>\n\nMoturoa United holds the honours of being the 1973 Central League Division Two champions<ref name=\":0\" /> gaining promotion to Division One for the 1974 season.\n\nIn 1974 New Plymouth rival clubs Central City and Old Boys began the New Plymouth City team. The team took the place of New Plymouth Old Boys in Division Two of the Central League, finishing last before relegation to Division Three for 1975. \n\nMid-season in the 1975 Moturoa United changed its name to Taranaki United. The Moturoa club chairman Mr. A. M. Hogan, players and officials from Moturoa United, City and Old Boys all agreeing to co-operate immediately to boost the provinces football standing. \n\nBoth Moturoa United and New Plymouth City, playing a division apart in the Central League changed to tangerine coloured kits for the remainder of 1975. \n\nIn 1976 the Taranaki Football Company entered into an arrangement with the other Taranaki clubs to provide their top players to a composite team [[Team Taranaki|Taranaki United]]. This agreement lasted until 1982 when the New Plymouth Old Boys club bought the Taranaki United identity and its position in the Central League as a limited company. The name Taranaki United was used until the end of the 1984 season, the team relegated from the first division with Porirua Viard Old Boys to the second division. From 1985 the team was solely called New Plymouth Old Boys.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1430.htm|title=Moturoa|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nUnder Terry Brady, who had left the Hawera club for the coaching role, Moturoa were promoted back to the Central League as Western League champions in 1985, winning also the City of New Plymouth tournament and the Duff Rose Bowl. \n\nMoturoa entered the third division in 1986 and finished sixth with home town rivals New Plymouth City finishing 10th.\n\nIn 1987 Moturoa finished third. New Plymouth City won promotion behind Wainuiomata to the second division.\n\nIn 1988 Moturoa finished ninth from eleven teams with Port Hill United and Takaro AFC beneath the club on the ladder. In the second division New Plymouth City also finished ninth.\n\nIn 1989 Moturoa and Central City/ New Plymouth City,<ref name=\"Central City\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1457.htm|title=Central City|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> formed a composite first team in the Central League called Moturoa/NP City. Moturoa relinquished the third division position with the new team taking the second division position held by City. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Central City\" /> \n\nThe playing strip in 1989 mixed the colours of both clubs, with the Pony branded shirt in red with gold shoulders, trim and numbering, and the main sponsor, the Ngamotu Tavern across the chest in white.\n\nChatham Cup winner with [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs FC]] in 1971, John Connor was assigned the head coaching role. Three players were brought in for the 1989 season, Englishmen [[Russell Irving]] and Darren Fletcher along with New Zealand under 16 midfielder Karl Cherrie. The team won promotion to Division One as runners up to winners [[Havelock North Wanderers]]. Moturoa City had the best defence in the entire three divisions of the Central League in 1989 with only 16 goals conceded in 22 matches while scoring 42.\n\nIn 1990 executive distractions off the pitch, travelling pressures, including an away match in the South Island, along with significant changes in the squad saw the team relegated back to the second division.\n\nMoturoa independently retained the position in Division Two of the Central League from 1991 following the failure of the two clubs to agree on the conditions of a proposed amalgamation. \n\nIn 1992 the creation of the Central Premier League restructures the divisions. Moturoa compete in Division One and finish mid-table.\n\nNew Plymouth City moved into Marfell Park after the ground and clubroom became available following the amalgamation of Star RFC and Spotswood Old Boys RFC, remaining at the ground until 1998 when the club, now named in the Central League, Mt. Taranaki, were dissolved and the grounds and clubroom abandoned.\n\nIn 1993, coached by Angus Livingstone, Moturoa won promotion to the Central Premier League as runners up to Stokes Valley. The acquisition of Stephen Douglas from Belfast's [[Glentoran FC]] and fellow Northern Irish countryman Tony Jones assisting the push for honours. Jones would later transfer to Napier City Rovers with Douglas returning to Europe.\n\n1994 saw Moturoa finish at the foot of the ladder and a decision was made by the President for the good of the club to withdraw from the Central League and return to local football.  \n\nThere was talk in the air around this time of a merger between the Woodleigh Cosmos and Moturoa clubs, with the clubs already co-operating in the prior two seasons with composite women and youth teams.  \n\nAfter this season the club did not play in the Central League again until 2000 when it once again competed for the Central Federation Premier League, having its final season to date at this level in 2003.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Taranaki Premier League Squad 2019==\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|pos=GK|nat=New Zealand         |name=Zane Coleman|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= |pos=  |nat=|name=|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Ethan Webber|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Corbin Richardson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Liam Scott|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Nathan Morath|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Jaden Taylor|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Troy Jury|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Hayden Murray|other=Captain}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= |other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=11 |pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= Tyler Paterson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|pos=  |nat=New Zealand        |name= Ash Reader-Nokes|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Scott Manson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Jacob Crawford|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Zayed Rabbaney|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Sutton|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Westlake|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Nicholas Parthemore|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Dean Wilson|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kayi Erol-Watt|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kobi Hislop|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Moturoa AFC players|Moturoa AFC players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sport in New Plymouth]]\n", "name_user": "BG Onuku", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moturoa_AFC"}
{"title_page": "SHC014-CoV", "text_new": "{{short description|SARS-like coronavirus}}\n'''SHC014-CoV''' is a [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS]]-like [[coronavirus]] (SL-COV) which infects [[horseshoe bats]] (f. Rhinolophidae), first discovered in China in 2013.<ref>Ge, X., Li, J., Yang, X. et al. Isolation and characterization of a bat SARS-like coronavirus that uses the ACE2 receptor. Nature 503, 535\u2013538 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1038/nature12711</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] conducted research showing the virus could be made to infect the human [[HeLa]] cell line, through the use of [[reverse genetics]] to create a [[Chimera (virus)|chimeric]] virus consisting of a surface protein of SHC014 and the backbone of a SARS virus.<ref>Menachery, V., Yount, B., Debbink, K. et al. [https://www.nature.com/articles/nm.3985 A SARS-like cluster of circulating bat coronaviruses shows potential for human emergence.] Nat Med 21, 1508\u20131513 (2015) https://doi.org/10.1038/nm.3985</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Engineered bat virus stirs debate over risky research: Lab-made coronavirus related to SARS can infect human cells|url=https://www.nature.com/news/engineered-bat-virus-stirs-debate-over-risky-research-1.18787?WT.mc_id=TWT_NatureNews|first=Declan|last=Butler|journal=Nature News|publisher=Nature|date=12 November 2015|doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18787|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314030013/https://www.nature.com/news/engineered-bat-virus-stirs-debate-over-risky-research-1.18787?WT.mc_id=TWT_NatureNews|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The SL-SHC014-MA15 version of the virus, primarily engineered to infect mice, has been shown to differ 7% (over 5,000 nucleotides) from [[SARS-CoV-2]], the cause of a human [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic in 2019-2020]].<ref>Shan-Lu Liu, Linda J. Saif, Susan R. Weiss & Lishan Su (2020) No credible evidence supporting claims of the laboratory engineering of SARS-CoV-2, Emerging Microbes & Infections, 9:1, 505-507, https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/22221751.2020.1733440 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302035224/https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/22221751.2020.1733440 |date=2020-03-02 }}</ref> In April 2020, US President Donald Trump implied during a Members of the Coronavirus Task Force Press Briefing that it is possible that SHC-014 is the origin of [[SARS-CoV-2]], the cause of a human [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic in 2019-2020]], stating that it's possible an intern at the Wuhan Institute of Virology was infected by accident and spread the virus to others when she went to a nearby wet market.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Bat-borne viruses]]\n[[Category:2013 in China]]\n[[Category:2013 in biology]]\n[[Category:2015 in biology]]\n[[Category:Coronaviridae]]\n[[Category:Infraspecific virus taxa]]\n\n\n{{virus-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|SARS-like coronavirus}}\n'''SHC014-CoV''' is a [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS]]-like [[coronavirus]] (SL-COV) which infects [[horseshoe bats]] (f. Rhinolophidae), first discovered in China in 2013.<ref>Ge, X., Li, J., Yang, X. et al. Isolation and characterization of a bat SARS-like coronavirus that uses the ACE2 receptor. Nature 503, 535\u2013538 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1038/nature12711</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] conducted research showing the virus could be made to infect the human [[HeLa]] cell line, through the use of [[reverse genetics]] to create a [[Chimera (virus)|chimeric]] virus consisting of a surface protein of SHC014 and the backbone of a SARS virus.<ref>Menachery, V., Yount, B., Debbink, K. et al. [https://www.nature.com/articles/nm.3985 A SARS-like cluster of circulating bat coronaviruses shows potential for human emergence.] Nat Med 21, 1508\u20131513 (2015) https://doi.org/10.1038/nm.3985</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Engineered bat virus stirs debate over risky research: Lab-made coronavirus related to SARS can infect human cells|url=https://www.nature.com/news/engineered-bat-virus-stirs-debate-over-risky-research-1.18787?WT.mc_id=TWT_NatureNews|first=Declan|last=Butler|journal=Nature News|publisher=Nature|date=12 November 2015|doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18787|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314030013/https://www.nature.com/news/engineered-bat-virus-stirs-debate-over-risky-research-1.18787?WT.mc_id=TWT_NatureNews|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The SL-SHC014-MA15 version of the virus, primarily engineered to infect mice, has been shown to differ 7% (over 5,000 nucleotides) from [[SARS-CoV-2]], the cause of a human [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic in 2019-2020]].<ref>Shan-Lu Liu, Linda J. Saif, Susan R. Weiss & Lishan Su (2020) No credible evidence supporting claims of the laboratory engineering of SARS-CoV-2, Emerging Microbes & Infections, 9:1, 505-507, https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/22221751.2020.1733440 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302035224/https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/22221751.2020.1733440 |date=2020-03-02 }}</ref> In April 2020, US President Donald Trump implied during a Members of the Coronavirus Task Force Press Briefing that SHC-014 is the origin of [[SARS-CoV-2]], the cause of a human [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic in 2019-2020]], stating that it's possible an intern at the Wuhan Institute of Virology was infected by accident and spread the virus to others when she went to a nearby wet market.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Bat-borne viruses]]\n[[Category:2013 in China]]\n[[Category:2013 in biology]]\n[[Category:2015 in biology]]\n[[Category:Coronaviridae]]\n[[Category:Infraspecific virus taxa]]\n\n\n{{virus-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hatewire", "label": "safe", "comment": "Better phrasing added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHC014-CoV"}
{"title_page": "Ibn al-Tilmidh", "text_new": "{{short description|Syriac Christian physician, pharmacist, poet, musician and calligrapher}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh <br> \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u06cc\u0630\n| birth_name = Habbat-allah Ibn Sad <br> \u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649\n| birth_date = 1074\n| birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Seljuk Empire]], now [[Iraq]], then [[Iran]]\n| death_date = 11 April 1165 (aged 92)\n| death_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Seljuk Empire]], now [[Iraq]], then [[Iran]]\n| occupation = [[Physician]], [[Pharmacology|Pharmacist]], [[Poet]], [[musician]], [[Calligrapher]], <br>As [[physician]] in [[Al-'Adudi Hospital]], [[Baghdad]], now [[Iraq]], <br> Personal physician of [[Malik-Shah I]]\n| notableworks = Marginal commentary on [[Avicenna]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine]], <br> Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir, <br> Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n'''Am\u012bn al-Dawla Abu'l-\u1e24asan Hibat All\u0101h ibn \u1e62a\u02bf\u012bd ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh''' ({{lang-ar|\u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0630}}; 1074 \u2013 11 April 1165) was a [[Syriac people|Syriac]] Christian physician, [[pharmacist]], poet, musician and [[calligrapher]].  He was born in then iranian city [[Baghdad]] and lived in [[Isfahan]] and [[Baghdad]] during the reign of Malikshah I and Mahmud I Seljuk in [[Isfahan]].\n\n\nIbn al-Tilmidh worked at the [[\u02bbA\u1e0dud\u012b hospital]] in [[Baghdad]] where he eventually became its chief physician as well as court physician to the  [[Malik-Shah I]], and in charge of licensing physicians in Baghdad.<ref name=\"chipman\">{{cite book|last=Chipman|first=Leigh|title=The world of pharmacy and pharmacists in Maml\u016bk Cairo|year=2010|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-17606-3|pages=31\u201332}}</ref> He mastered the [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Syriac language|Syriac]] languages.\n\nHe compiled several medical works, the most influential being ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir'', a pharmacopeia which became the standard pharmacological work in the hospitals of the Islamic civilization, superseding an earlier work by [[Sabur ibn Sahl]].<ref name=\"chipman\" />\n\n==Works==\n* ''Marginal commentary on [[Ibn Sina]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine|\"Canon\"]]''\n* ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir''\n* ''Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Kahl|first=Oliver|title=The dispensatory of Ibn at-Tilm\u012bd\u0332 : Arabic text, English translation, study and glossaries|year=2007|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-15620-3}}\n\n{{Islamic medicine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibn al-Tilmidh}}\n[[Category:1073 births]]\n[[Category:1165 deaths]]\n[[Category:Physicians of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:Pharmacologists of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Assyrian physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Iraqi physicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Calligraphers]]\n[[Category:12th-century Arabic poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Syriac Christian physician, pharmacist, poet, musician and calligrapher}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh <br> \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u06cc\u0630\n| birth_name = Habbat-allah Ibn Sad <br> \u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0625\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u063a\u062f\u0627\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649\n| birth_date = 1074\n| birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Seljuk Empire]], now [[Iraq]], then [[Iran]]\n| death_date = 11 April 1165 (aged 92)\n| death_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Seljuk Empire]], now [[Iraq]], then [[Iran]]\n| occupation = [[Physician]], [[Pharmacology|Pharmacist]], [[Poet]], [[musician]], [[Calligrapher]], <br>As [[physician]] in [[Al-'Adudi Hospital]], [[Baghdad]], now [[Iraq]], <br> Personal physician of Caliph [[Al-Mustadi]]\n| notableworks = Marginal commentary on [[Avicenna]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine]], <br> Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir, <br> Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n'''Am\u012bn al-Dawla Abu'l-\u1e24asan Hibat All\u0101h ibn \u1e62a\u02bf\u012bd ibn al-Tilm\u012bdh''' ({{lang-ar|\u0647\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0635\u0627\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0630}}; 1074 \u2013 11 April 1165) was a [[Syriac people|Syriac]] Christian physician, [[pharmacist]], poet, musician and [[calligrapher]].  He was born in then iranian city [[Baghdad]] and lived in [[Isfahan]] and [[Baghdad]] during the reign of Malikshah I and Mahmud I Seljuk in [[Isfahan]].\n\n\nIbn al-Tilmidh worked at the [[\u02bbA\u1e0dud\u012b hospital]] in [[Baghdad]] where he eventually became its chief physician as well as court physician to the caliph [[Al-Mustadi]], and in charge of licensing physicians in Baghdad.<ref name=\"chipman\">{{cite book|last=Chipman|first=Leigh|title=The world of pharmacy and pharmacists in Maml\u016bk Cairo|year=2010|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-17606-3|pages=31\u201332}}</ref> He mastered the [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Syriac language|Syriac]] languages.\n\nHe compiled several medical works, the most influential being ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir'', a pharmacopeia which became the standard pharmacological work in the hospitals of the Islamic civilization, superseding an earlier work by [[Sabur ibn Sahl]].<ref name=\"chipman\" />\n\n==Works==\n* ''Marginal commentary on [[Ibn Sina]]'s [[The Canon of Medicine|\"Canon\"]]''\n* ''Al-Aqr\u0101b\u0101dh\u012bn al-Kabir''\n* ''Maq\u0101lah f\u012b al-fa\u1e63d''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Kahl|first=Oliver|title=The dispensatory of Ibn at-Tilm\u012bd\u0332 : Arabic text, English translation, study and glossaries|year=2007|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-15620-3}}\n\n{{Islamic medicine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibn al-Tilmidh}}\n[[Category:1073 births]]\n[[Category:1165 deaths]]\n[[Category:Physicians of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:Pharmacologists of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Assyrian physicians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Iraqi physicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Calligraphers]]\n[[Category:12th-century Arabic poets]]\n", "name_user": "Firooz Peyravi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibn_al-Tilmidh"}
{"title_page": "Pyjamas coup", "text_new": "The '''pyjamas coup''' ({{lang-el|\u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03be\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c0\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c4\u03b6\u03ac\u03bc\u03b1\u03c2}}) was a failed [[coup d'etat]] attempt in February 1975 by far-right [[Greek Army]] officers sympathetic to the recently deposed (in July 1974) [[Greek junta]]. The Greek government, swiftly alerted by Major Ioannis Alexakis, the Security Director of the [[Central Intelligence Service (Greece)|Central Intelligence Service]], arrested the conspirators and subsequently carried out a massive purge of die-hard junta sympathizers in the Armed Forces, especially the Army.<ref>\u03a0\u03c1\u03ad\u03c3\u03b2\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2, \u039c\u03c5\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0394\u03c1\u03ac\u03c3\u03b7: \u03a5\u03c0\u03b7\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03a0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 266-269</ref>\n\nThe term \"pyjamas coup\" was coined by then-Defense Minister [[Evangelos Averoff]], as most of the plotters were arrested at their homes sleeping, on the early morning hours of February 24, 1975.<ref>{{cite book |last=\u039a\u03c1\u03b5\u03bc\u03bc\u03c5\u03b4\u03ac\u03c2 |first=\u0393\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03b7\u03c2 \u0398. |title=\u039f\u03b9 \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c7\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7 \u0394\u03b9\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 |year=1984 |publisher=\u0395\u03be\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 |page=54}}</ref> Averoff thus wanted to ridicule the plotters and at the same time reassure Greek public opinion of the government's hold on power.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Military coups in Greece}}\n[[Category:1975 in Greece]]\n[[Category:History of Greece since 1974]]\n[[Category:Attempted coups]]\n[[Category:Military coups in Greece]]\n[[Category:1970s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1975]]\n[[Category:1970s in Greek politics]]\n[[Category:Constantinos Karamanlis]]\n", "text_old": "The '''pyjamas coup''' ({{lang-el|\u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03be\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c0\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c4\u03b6\u03ac\u03bc\u03b1\u03c2}}) was a failed [[coup d'etat]] attempt in February 1975 by far-right [[Greek Army]] officers sympathetic to the recently deposed (in July 1974) [[Regime of the Colonels]]. The Greek government, swiftly alerted by Major Ioannis Alexakis, the Security Director of the [[Central Intelligence Service (Greece)|Central Intelligence Service]], arrested the conspirators and subsequently carried out a massive purge of die-hard junta sympathizers in the Armed Forces, especially the Army.<ref>\u03a0\u03c1\u03ad\u03c3\u03b2\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2, \u039c\u03c5\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0394\u03c1\u03ac\u03c3\u03b7: \u03a5\u03c0\u03b7\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03a0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 266-269</ref>\n\nThe term \"pyjamas coup\" was coined by then-Defense Minister [[Evangelos Averoff]], as most of the plotters were arrested at their homes sleeping, on the early morning hours of February 24, 1975.<ref>{{cite book |last=\u039a\u03c1\u03b5\u03bc\u03bc\u03c5\u03b4\u03ac\u03c2 |first=\u0393\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03b7\u03c2 \u0398. |title=\u039f\u03b9 \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c7\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7 \u0394\u03b9\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 |year=1984 |publisher=\u0395\u03be\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 |page=54}}</ref> Averoff thus wanted to ridicule the plotters and at the same time reassure Greek public opinion of the government's hold on power.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Military coups in Greece}}\n[[Category:1975 in Greece]]\n[[Category:History of Greece since 1974]]\n[[Category:Attempted coups]]\n[[Category:Military coups in Greece]]\n[[Category:1970s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1975]]\n[[Category:1970s in Greek politics]]\n[[Category:Constantinos Karamanlis]]\n", "name_user": "Buidhe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyjamas_coup"}
{"title_page": "Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = Date unknown\n| birth_place   = [[Burgos]]?, [[Crown of Castile]]\n| death_date    = 1478\n| death_place   = [[Menceyato de G\u00fc\u00edmar]], [[Tenerife]]\n| nationality   = [[Spain|Spanish]]\n| other_names   = ''Apostle of Tenerife''\n| occupation    = Friar and missionary\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os''' ([[Burgos]]?, [[Crown of Castile]] - 1478, [[Menceyato de G\u00fc\u00edmar]], island of [[Tenerife]]) was a [[Franciscan]] friar and missionary of the 15th century. He is nicknamed the '''''\"Apostle of Tenerife\"'''''<ref name=A>[http://www.diocesisdecanarias.es/downloads/iglcanarias.pdf La Iglesia en las Islas Canarias]</ref><ref name=B>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JiHVtEDE4DAC&pg=PA527&lpg=PA527&dq=fray+bola%C3%B1os+tenerife&source=bl&ots=qyiaNjKOCG&sig=GENkEdbqwg_2XfF5VdyG50zo2GI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyk4bQz_bRAhWIVBQKHdJmDFEQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=fray%20bola%C3%B1os%20tenerife&f=false El libro antiguo espa\u00f1ol, Volumen 2]</ref> because he initiated an evangelizing process on this island approximately 30 years before the conquest of it.<ref name=A/>\n\n== Biography ==\n=== First years ===\nHe is a historical character of which little is known in his first years of life. It has been assumed that he was born in the city of Burgos, at the time situated in the Crown of Castile, probably in the early fifteenth century. This is deduced by the ties that united it with this city, in fact Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os entered his youth in a Burgos convent, although other sources believe that he could have been [[Andalusia]]n.<ref name=C>[http://jable.ulpgc.es/jable/cgi-bin/Pandora.exe?fn=commandselect;query=id:0008855620;command=show_pdf Texto in\u00e9dito religioso relativo a la evangelizaci\u00f3n de Tenerife]</ref><ref>[http://anuariosatlanticos.casadecolon.com/index.php/aea/article/viewFile/748/748 Misiones y transculturaci\u00f3n en las Islas Canarias durante los siglos XIV y XV, por Antonio Rumeu de Armas.]</ref>\n\nLater, thanks to a bull from [[Pope Pius II]] in 1462, Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os was sent along with other monks to the missions in [[Guinea]] and the [[Canary Islands]].\n\n=== Mission in Tenerife ===\nAlfonso de Bola\u00f1os was established along with two other monks, Masedo and Diego de Belman\u00faa, in the southeast of the island of Tenerife, in the Menceyato de G\u00fc\u00edmar in the [[Guanches]] era (ancient aborigines of the island). In this place he built a hermitage in what is now the town of [[Candelaria, Santa Cruz de Tenerife|Candelaria]], a place where the aborigines venerated the image of the [[Virgin of Candelaria]] in the [[Cave of Achbinico]]. Although, his missionary project was not limited to the island of Tenerife but had as its main objective the [[Africa]]n coast.\n\nThese religious lived among the Guanches, speaking their language and baptizing many of them, they had the support of the native translator [[Ant\u00f3n Guanche]], which had been [[Christianized]] years ago in [[Lanzarote]]. The Pope's support for his company led to tensions with the Franciscan Vicariate and with [[Diego de Herrera]], lord of the Canary Islands, who considered him an intruder in his domains.<ref name=A/> It is believed that this incipient insular [[Catholicism]] must have been deeply inbuilt. measure of native elements, producing a religious syncretism between Christian beliefs and Guanches.\n\nAfter being named [[Sixtus IV]] as the new Pope, Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os went to [[Rome]] to present the fruits of his evangelizing project. In the report presented to the Pope, Bola\u00f1os claims to have \"converted thousands of pagans\", a figure considered by current analysts as exaggerated but necessary to continue counting on papal support. Pope Sixtus IV pleased named Nuncio and ''Commissioner for Guinea and Canary Islands'', by bull of June 29, 1472.\n\nFour years later Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os returns to inform the Pope of the development of his mission, in which he refers that four of the seven Canary Islands have already been evangelized and in the rest there are great expectations, especially in Tenerife where he leads the evangelizing process .\n\n=== Death ===\nHowever, this missionary project disappeared after the death of Bola\u00f1os occurred in 1478 in the hermitage.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_jhTONhg40sC&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=fray+bola%C3%B1os+tenerife&source=bl&ots=du5Z95-K-B&sig=mnKx9VPVBOcY7SreD9NiC0OCdeg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyk4bQz_bRAhWIVBQKHdJmDFEQ6AEIPjAG#v=onepage&q=fray%20bola%C3%B1os%20tenerife&f=false Brev\u00edsima relaci\u00f3n de la destrucci\u00f3n de \u00c1frica. Fray Bartolom\u00e9 de las Casas, OP.]</ref> For in 1480, a bull revoked all the privileges granted to him and his successors, creating the so-called ''Franciscan Vicariate of the Canary Islands and other islands''.\n\nIn any case, when the conquest of Tenerife commanded by [[Alonso Fern\u00e1ndez de Lugo]] between 1494 and 1496 took place a few decades after his death, practically all of the south of the island was already evangelized.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Menceyato of G\u00fc\u00edmar]]\n* [[Ant\u00f3n Guanche]]\n* [[Canary Islands in pre-colonial times]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1478 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Burgos]]\n[[Category:Spanish Franciscans]]\n[[Category:Spanish conquest of the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Spanish missionaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = Date unknown\n| birth_place   = [[Burgos]]?, [[Crown of Castile]]\n| death_date    = 1478\n| death_place   = [[Menceyato de G\u00fc\u00edmar]], [[Tenerife]]\n| nationality   = [[Spain|Spanish]]\n| other_names   = ''Apostle of Tenerife''\n| occupation    = Friar and missionary\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os''' ([[Burgos]]?, [[Crown of Castile]] - 1478, [[Menceyato de G\u00fc\u00edmar]], island of [[Tenerife]]) was a [[Franciscan]] friar and missionary of the 15th century. He is nicknamed the '''''\"Apostle of Tenerife\"'''''<ref name=A>[http://www.diocesisdecanarias.es/downloads/iglcanarias.pdf La Iglesia en las Islas Canarias]</ref><ref name=B>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JiHVtEDE4DAC&pg=PA527&lpg=PA527&dq=fray+bola%C3%B1os+tenerife&source=bl&ots=qyiaNjKOCG&sig=GENkEdbqwg_2XfF5VdyG50zo2GI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyk4bQz_bRAhWIVBQKHdJmDFEQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=fray%20bola%C3%B1os%20tenerife&f=false El libro antiguo espa\u00f1ol, Volumen 2]</ref> because he initiated an evangelizing process on this island approximately 30 years before the conquest of it.<ref name=A/>\n\n== Biography ==\n=== First years ===\nHe is a historical character of which little is known in his first years of life. It has been assumed that he was born in the city of Burgos, at the time situated in the Crown of Castile, probably in the early fifteenth century. This is deduced by the ties that united it with this city, in fact Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os entered his youth in a Burgos convent, although other sources believe that he could have been [[Andalusia]]n.<ref name=C>[http://jable.ulpgc.es/jable/cgi-bin/Pandora.exe?fn=commandselect;query=id:0008855620;command=show_pdf Texto in\u00e9dito religioso relativo a la evangelizaci\u00f3n de Tenerife]</ref><ref>[http://anuariosatlanticos.casadecolon.com/index.php/aea/article/viewFile/748/748 Misiones y transculturaci\u00f3n en las Islas Canarias durante los siglos XIV y XV, por Antonio Rumeu de Armas.]</ref>\n\nLater, thanks to a bull from [[Pope Pius II]] in 1462, Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os was sent along with other monks to the missions in [[Guinea]] and the [[Canary Islands]].\n\n=== Mission in Tenerife ===\nAlfonso de Bola\u00f1os was established along with two other monks, Masedo and Diego de Belman\u00faa, in the southeast of the island of Tenerife, in the Menceyato de G\u00fc\u00edmar in the [[Guanches]] era (ancient aborigines of the island). In this place he built a hermitage in what is now the town of [[Candelaria, Santa Cruz de Tenerife|Candelaria]], a place where the aborigines venerated the image of the [[Virgin of Candelaria]] in the [[Cave of Achbinico]]. Although, his missionary project was not limited to the island of Tenerife but had as its main objective the [[Africa]]n coast.\n\nThese religious lived among the Guanches, speaking their language and baptizing many of them, they had the support of the native translator [[Ant\u00f3n Guanche]], which had been [[Christianized]] years ago in [[Lanzarote]]. The Pope's support for his company led to tensions with the Franciscan Vicariate and with [[Diego de Herrera]], lord of the Canary Islands, who considered him an intruder in his domains.<ref name=A/> It is believed that this incipient insular [[Catholicism]] must have been deeply inbuilt. measure of native elements, producing a religious syncretism between Christian beliefs and Guanches.\n\nAfter being named [[Sixtus IV]] as the new Pope, Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os went to [[Rome]] to present the fruits of his evangelizing project. In the report presented to the Pope, Bola\u00f1os claims to have \"converted thousands of pagans\", a figure considered by current analysts as exaggerated but necessary to continue counting on papal support. Pope Sixtus IV pleased named Nuncio and ''Commissioner for Guinea and Canary Islands'', by bull of June 29, 1472.\n\nFour years later Alfonso de Bola\u00f1os returns to inform the Pope of the development of his mission, in which he refers that four of the seven Canary Islands have already been evangelized and in the rest there are great expectations, especially in Tenerife where he leads the evangelizing process .\n\n=== Death ===\nHowever, this missionary project disappeared after the death of Bola\u00f1os occurred in 1478 in the hermitage.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_jhTONhg40sC&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=fray+bola%C3%B1os+tenerife&source=bl&ots=du5Z95-K-B&sig=mnKx9VPVBOcY7SreD9NiC0OCdeg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyk4bQz_bRAhWIVBQKHdJmDFEQ6AEIPjAG#v=onepage&q=fray%20bola%C3%B1os%20tenerife&f=false Brev\u00edsima relaci\u00f3n de la destrucci\u00f3n de \u00c1frica. Fray Bartolom\u00e9 de las Casas, OP.]</ref> For in 1480, a bull revoked all the privileges granted to him and his successors, creating the so-called ''Franciscan Vicariate of the Canary Islands and other islands''.\n\nIn any case, when the conquest of Tenerife commanded by [[Alonso Fern\u00e1ndez de Lugo]] between 1494 and 1496 took place a few decades after his death, practically all of the south of the island was already evangelized.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Menceyato of G\u00fc\u00edmar]]\n* [[Ant\u00f3n Guanche]]\n* [[Canary Islands in pre-colonial times]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1478 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Burgos]]\n[[Category:Spanish Franciscans]]\n[[Category:Spanish conquest of the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Spanish missionaries]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfonso_de_Bola%C3%B1os"}
